(33, 2, '2020-06-04 12:02:30', '2020-06-04 12:02:30', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In today‚Äôs online world, ensuring the security of your website is paramount. One of the most significant steps in securing your WordPress website is by enabling HTTPS (HyperText Transfer Protocol Secure) instead of the standard HTTP. HTTPS encrypts the communication between the browser and the server, which means all the data exchanged is securely transmitted. This is especially crucial for websites that handle sensitive information, such as user logins, forms, payments, and other personal data.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Migrating a website from HTTP to HTTPS not only improves security but also helps your website perform better in terms of SEO (Search Engine Optimization). Search engines like Google prioritize secure websites and reward them with a ranking boost. Furthermore, users are more likely to trust websites marked with a padlock icon in the browser\'s address bar, signaling that their data is secure.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While switching your WordPress site from HTTP to HTTPS might seem like a complex task, it is actually a straightforward process that can be accomplished in various ways. One of the most effective methods is by directly modifying the WordPress database to reflect the new HTTPS URL. In this blog, we will explain step-by-step how you can change your WordPress URL from HTTP to HTTPS using the database.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Why Move from HTTP to HTTPS?</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before delving into the details of how to change your WordPress URL from HTTP to HTTPS in the database, let‚Äôs first discuss why this migration is essential.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">1. <strong>Improved Security</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you switch from HTTP to HTTPS, data exchanged between the server and the browser is encrypted. This ensures that no sensitive data, such as passwords or credit card information, can be intercepted or tampered with during transmission. For WordPress sites, this is critical, especially for eCommerce websites and login pages.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">2. <strong>SEO Benefits</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Search engines like Google use HTTPS as a ranking signal. Websites that are secured with SSL certificates and use HTTPS generally get a small ranking boost compared to HTTP websites. In 2014, Google made HTTPS a ranking factor, and this has since become more important. Moving to HTTPS ensures your site is more discoverable and has better search engine visibility.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">3. <strong>Trust and User Confidence</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Browsers like Google Chrome display a ‚ÄúNot Secure‚Äù message in the address bar when users visit a site without HTTPS. This can make visitors uncomfortable and hesitant to interact with your site, especially if it requires login details or personal information. HTTPS builds trust with your users, who can see the padlock symbol next to the URL.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">4. <strong>Compliance and Legal Requirements</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Certain regulatory and legal frameworks require websites to handle data securely. If your site deals with personal user information, it may be required by law to use HTTPS. Websites using HTTPS are considered to be more compliant with data protection regulations, such as GDPR (General Data Protection Regulation) and PCI-DSS (Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Prerequisites for Changing WordPress URL to HTTPS via Database</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before making any changes to the database, there are a few prerequisites you should ensure:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>SSL Certificate</strong>: Make sure that your SSL certificate is installed correctly on your WordPress website. You can get an SSL certificate from your web host, or you can use a free service like Let‚Äôs Encrypt. If you‚Äôre unsure whether your SSL certificate is properly installed, you can check by visiting your website with <code>https://</code> (for example, <code>https://www.yoursite.com</code>), and your browser should display a secure padlock symbol in the address bar.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Access to phpMyAdmin</strong>: To modify the database, you need access to phpMyAdmin, which is a database management tool provided by most web hosting providers. You can access phpMyAdmin through your hosting account‚Äôs cPanel.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Backup Your Database</strong>: <strong>Backing up your WordPress database is crucial</strong> before making any changes. In case something goes wrong, you can easily restore your website to its previous state. You can use plugins like UpdraftPlus or perform a manual backup via phpMyAdmin.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Steps to Change WordPress URL from HTTP to HTTPS in the Database</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once you‚Äôve ensured that the SSL certificate is installed and you‚Äôve backed up your website, you can begin the process of changing your WordPress URL from HTTP to HTTPS in the database. There are two main methods for doing this: directly editing the database using SQL queries and using phpMyAdmin to make the necessary changes manually.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 1: Log into Your Hosting Account</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The first step is to log into your hosting account. Typically, WordPress websites are hosted on platforms like cPanel, Plesk, or other hosting management systems. Once logged in, navigate to the <strong>phpMyAdmin</strong> tool. This tool allows you to interact with your WordPress database and make changes directly.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 2: Open phpMyAdmin and Select Your WordPress Database</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After logging in to phpMyAdmin, you‚Äôll see a list of all databases associated with your hosting account. Locate the database for your WordPress website, which is typically named something like <code>wp_database</code> or <code>yoursite_db</code>. Click on the database to open it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 3: Edit the wp_options Table</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the left-hand menu, under your WordPress database, locate and click on the <strong>wp_options</strong> table. This table holds several key configuration options for your WordPress site, including the <strong>siteurl</strong> and <strong>home</strong> values, which define your website‚Äôs URL.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Look for the <strong>siteurl</strong> and <strong>home</strong> rows. These are the values that define your website\'s base URL and need to be updated to HTTPS.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Click the <strong>Edit</strong> button (the pencil icon) next to each row, and you will be able to modify the <code>option_value</code> field.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>In the <strong>option_value</strong> field for both rows, change the <code>http://</code> to <code>https://</code>. For example, change:<code>http://yoursite.com</code> to <code>https://yoursite.com</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Once you‚Äôve made the changes, click <strong>Go</strong> to save the changes.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 4: Update URLs in the Database</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To fully switch your site to HTTPS, you need to update all internal references to your old HTTP URL throughout the WordPress database. These include URLs found in post content, media links, and other database tables. For this, you‚Äôll need to run a series of SQL queries.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here are the queries you should run in phpMyAdmin:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>UPDATE wp_options SET option_value = replace(option_value, \'http://codenskills.com\', \'https://codenskills.com\') WHERE option_name = \'home\' OR option_name = \'siteurl\';\n\nUPDATE wp_postmeta SET meta_value = replace(meta_value,\'http://codenskills.com\',\'https://codenskills.com\');\nUPDATE wp_posts SET guid = replace(guid, \'http://codenskills.com\',\'https://codenskills.com\');\n\nUPDATE wp_posts SET post_content = replace(post_content, \'http://codenskills.com\',\'https://codenskills.com\');\n\nUPDATE wp_posts SET pinged = REPLACE(pinged, \'http://codenskills.com\', \'https://codenskills.com\')WHERE pinged LIKE \'%http://codenskills.com%\';\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>These queries will replace all instances of the HTTP URL with the new HTTPS URL across various tables in your WordPress database.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 5: Update URLs in Page Builders (Optional)</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you are using a page builder like WPBakery or Elementor, you may need to run additional queries to replace URLs embedded in page builder content.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For WPBakery, run these queries:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>\nUPDATE wp_posts SET post_content = REPLACE(post_content, \'src=\"http://codenskills.com\', \'src=\"https://codenskills.com\')WHERE post_content LIKE \'%src=\"http://codenskills.com%\';\n\nUPDATE wp_posts SET post_content = REPLACE(post_content, \"src=\'http://codenskills.com\", \"src=\'https://codenskills.com\")WHERE post_content LIKE \"%src=\'http://codenskills.com%\";\n\nUPDATE wp_posts SET post_content = REPLACE(post_content, \'href=\"http://codenskills.com\', \'href=\"https://codenskills.com\')WHERE post_content LIKE \'%href=\"http://codenskills.com%\';\n\nUPDATE wp_posts SET post_content = REPLACE(post_content, \"href=\'http://codenskills.com\", \"href=\'https://codenskills.com\")WHERE post_content LIKE \"%href=\'http://codenskills.com%\";\n\n\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 6: Clear Cache and Verify Changes</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once you‚Äôve made the necessary database changes, you should clear your website‚Äôs cache to ensure that visitors see the updated HTTPS URLs. If you are using a caching plugin, such as W3 Total Cache or WP Super Cache, clear the cache from within the plugin settings.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Additionally, clear your browser cache to ensure that you‚Äôre seeing the most recent version of your website.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Finally, verify that the changes were successful by visiting your website using HTTPS. Check if the site loads without any security warnings and confirm that all internal links now use HTTPS.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Conclusion</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Changing your WordPress URL from HTTP to HTTPS is an essential step toward improving your website‚Äôs security, SEO, and user trust. While there are several methods to achieve this, updating the URLs in the database is a direct and effective approach. By following the steps outlined in this blog, you can safely and efficiently switch your WordPress website to HTTPS and ensure that your site operates securely and efficiently.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Remember to always back up your website before making changes, and if you encounter any issues, seek help from a professional developer or your hosting provider. With HTTPS in place, you‚Äôll enjoy enhanced security and better search engine visibility.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-buttons\"><!-- wp:button -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-button\"><a class=\"wp-block-button__link wp-element-button\" href=\"https://codenskills.com/how-to-force-redirect-http-to-https-in-wordpress-via-htaccess/\">How to force redirect HTTP to HTTPS in WordPress via htaccess</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons -->', 'How to change WordPress  URL HTTP to HTTPS  from database', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'how-to-change-http-to-https-wordpress-url-from-database', '', '', '2025-03-03 09:39:34', '2025-03-03 09:39:34', '', 0, 'https://mycodingsolution.com/?p=33', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(39, 2, '2020-06-06 12:01:01', '2020-06-06 12:01:01', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you are building a WordPress theme and want to integrate a <strong>Bootstrap menu</strong>, you need to customize the WordPress menu structure. By default, WordPress generates a menu structure that doesn‚Äôt fully match Bootstrap\'s format. However, using the <strong>Walker Class</strong>, we can transform the WordPress menu into a Bootstrap-compatible menu.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In this article, we‚Äôll go step by step on how to use a <strong>custom Walker class</strong> to create a <strong>Bootstrap menu in WordPress</strong>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Why Use a Walker Class for Menus?</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A <strong>Walker Class</strong> in WordPress is a way to customize the HTML output of hierarchical structures such as menus, categories, and comments. In this case, we‚Äôll use a Walker class to modify the WordPress menu markup to align with <strong>Bootstrap\'s dropdown structure</strong>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 1: Define a Custom Walker Class in <code>functions.php</code></strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We will create a custom class named <code>submenu_wrapper</code> by extending the <code>Walker_Nav_Menu</code> class. This will help us customize the output of WordPress menus.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Add the following code to your <code>functions.php</code> file:</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>class submenu_wrapper extends Walker_Nav_Menu {\n    // Add classes to &lt;ul> sub-menus\n    function start_lvl( &amp;$output, $depth = 0, $args = array() ) {\n        $indent = ($depth > 0 ? str_repeat(\"\\t\", $depth) : \'\'); // Code indent\n        $display_depth = ($depth + 1); // First submenu is depth 0\n\n        // Define classes for sub-menus\n        $classes = array(\'dropdown-menu\');\n        $class_names = implode(\' \', $classes);\n\n        // Build the submenu HTML\n        if ($display_depth == 1) {\n            $output .= \"\\n\" . $indent . \'&lt;ul class=\"\' . $class_names . \'\">\' . \"\\n\";\n        } else {\n            $output .= \"\\n\" . $indent . \'&lt;ul class=\"\' . $class_names . \'\">\' . \"\\n\";\n        }\n    }\n}\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>What This Code Does:</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Extends the <code>Walker_Nav_Menu</code> class.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Modifies the <strong>submenu (<code>&lt;ul></code>) output</strong> by adding the Bootstrap class <code>dropdown-menu</code>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Ensures <strong>nested menus</strong> work correctly.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 2: Add Bootstrap-Compatible Classes to Menu Links</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To make our menu fully compatible with Bootstrap, we need to modify the <code>&lt;a&gt;</code> tags inside our menu items. WordPress provides the <code>nav_menu_link_attributes</code> filter to modify menu link attributes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Add the following function to your <code>functions.php</code> file:</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>add_filter(\'nav_menu_link_attributes\', \'anchor_menu_add_class\', 10, 4);\nfunction anchor_menu_add_class($atts, $item, $args, $depth = 0) {\n    // Check if the menu item has children and is at depth 0\n    if ($args->walker->has_children == 1 &amp;&amp; $depth === 0) {\n        $atts&#91;\'href\'] = !empty($item->url) ? $item->url : \'\';\n        $atts&#91;\'data-toggle\'] = \'dropdown\';\n        $atts&#91;\'class\'] = \'dropdown-toggle\';\n        $atts&#91;\'aria-haspopup\'] = \'true\';\n        $atts&#91;\'aria-expanded\'] = \'false\';\n    } elseif ($depth === 0) {\n        $atts&#91;\'href\'] = !empty($item->url) ? $item->url : \'\';\n        $atts&#91;\'class\'] = \'nav-link\';\n    } elseif ($depth === 1) {\n        $atts&#91;\'href\'] = !empty($item->url) ? $item->url : \'\';\n        $atts&#91;\'class\'] = \'dropdown-item\';\n    }\n    return $atts;\n}\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>What This Code Does:</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Adds Bootstrap‚Äôs <code>dropdown-toggle</code> class to parent menu items with children.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Ensures top-level items have the <code>nav-link</code> class.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Adds the <code>dropdown-item</code> class to submenu links.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Uses <code>data-toggle=\"dropdown\"</code> for Bootstrap functionality.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 3: Call the Walker Class in <code>header.php</code></strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now that we have our <strong>Walker Class</strong> and <strong>custom attributes for menu links</strong>, we need to call it when rendering the menu in <code>header.php</code>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Replace the default <code>wp_nav_menu()</code> function with the following:</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;?php \necho wp_nav_menu(array(\n    \'menu\' => \'Home Menu\',\n    \'menu_class\' => \'navbar-nav ml-auto\',\n    \'walker\' => new submenu_wrapper(),\n    \'container\' => false\n)); \n?>\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>What This Code Does:</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Calls the WordPress menu named <code>\"Home Menu\"</code>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Uses the <strong>custom walker class</strong> (<code>submenu_wrapper</code>).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Adds the Bootstrap class <code>navbar-nav ml-auto</code>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Removes the default <code>div</code> container (<code>container => false</code>).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 4: Add Active Class to the Current Menu Item</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To highlight the active menu item, WordPress assigns the class <code>current-menu-item</code>. However, we can make it more Bootstrap-friendly.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Add this code to <code>functions.php</code>:</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>add_filter(\'nav_menu_css_class\', \'add_active_class_to_menu\', 10, 2);\nfunction add_active_class_to_menu($classes, $item) {\n    if (in_array(\'current-menu-item\', $classes)) {\n        $classes&#91;] = \'active\';\n    }\n    return $classes;\n}\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>What This Code Does:</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Checks if the menu item has the <strong>current-menu-item</strong> class.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>If so, it adds the Bootstrap <code>active</code> class to highlight it.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 5: Add Bootstrap Navbar Structure</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Make sure your menu is wrapped inside the Bootstrap navbar structure in <code>header.php</code>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;nav class=\"navbar navbar-expand-lg navbar-light bg-light\">\n    &lt;a class=\"navbar-brand\" href=\"#\">Your Logo&lt;/a>\n    &lt;button class=\"navbar-toggler\" type=\"button\" data-toggle=\"collapse\" data-target=\"#navbarNav\"\n        aria-controls=\"navbarNav\" aria-expanded=\"false\" aria-label=\"Toggle navigation\">\n        &lt;span class=\"navbar-toggler-icon\">&lt;/span>\n    &lt;/button>\n    &lt;div class=\"collapse navbar-collapse\" id=\"navbarNav\">\n        &lt;?php \n        echo wp_nav_menu(array(\n            \'menu\' => \'Home Menu\',\n            \'menu_class\' => \'navbar-nav ml-auto\',\n            \'walker\' => new submenu_wrapper(),\n            \'container\' => false\n        )); \n        ?>\n    &lt;/div>\n&lt;/nav>\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Final Thoughts</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By following these steps, we have successfully converted a <strong>WordPress menu into a Bootstrap menu</strong> using the <strong>Walker Class</strong>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Key Features Implemented:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Used a <strong>Walker Class</strong> to modify the <strong>menu structure</strong>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Added Bootstrap classes (<code>dropdown-menu</code>, <code>dropdown-toggle</code>, <code>dropdown-item</code>).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Integrated the menu into <strong>Bootstrap‚Äôs navbar</strong>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Added an <code>active</code> class to highlight the <strong>current menu item</strong>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":176,\"width\":\"823px\",\"height\":\"129px\",\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large is-resized\"><img src=\"https://codenskills.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/05/Screenshot_2021-05-27_18_29_48-1024x162.png\" alt=\"Bootstrap Menu\" class=\"wp-image-176\" style=\"width:823px;height:129px\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><br>   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-buttons\"><!-- wp:button -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-button\"><a class=\"wp-block-button__link wp-element-button\" href=\"https://codenskills.com/how-to-add-active-class-in-wordpress-bootstrap-menu-using-hook/\">Add Active class in wordpress menu by hook </a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons -->', 'How To Convert HTML Bootstrap Menu In WordPress', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'how-to-convert-html-bootstrap-menu-in-wordpress', '', '', '2025-03-03 08:14:58', '2025-03-03 08:14:58', '', 0, 'https://mycodingsolution.com/?p=39', 0, 'post', '', 0);
