(72, 2, '2020-06-27 09:50:25', '2020-06-27 09:50:25', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When building websites with WordPress and Bootstrap, one of the most common tasks you might encounter is adding an <strong>active class</strong> to the menu items when they are clicked or visited by the user. This is important for user navigation and helps in highlighting the current section or page they are on, offering a better user experience.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Bootstrap, which is one of the most popular front-end frameworks, makes it easy to create beautiful, responsive menus. However, by default, WordPress does not automatically add the \"active\" class to the menu item that corresponds to the current page. Fortunately, WordPress provides a convenient way to modify the output of WordPress menus through filters and hooks. In this blog, we‚Äôll guide you on how to use the <code>nav_menu_css_class</code> filter to add the \"active\" class to WordPress Bootstrap menus.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>What is the Active Class?</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before diving into the technicalities, let‚Äôs first understand the role of the \"active\" class in web development.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Bootstrap‚Äôs Active Class</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In Bootstrap, the \"active\" class is used to highlight a menu item, indicating that it‚Äôs the current page or section the user is on. This class is typically applied to navigation links, tabs, buttons, and other elements to provide a visual cue to the user.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For instance, when a user clicks on a menu item, that item should be highlighted with the active class to indicate the current page. This helps users know where they are on the website and allows them to quickly navigate between sections.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Why Use Hooks to Modify WordPress Menus?</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>WordPress provides a set of built-in functions, hooks, and filters that developers can use to modify the default behavior and output of the platform. This allows you to customize WordPress functionality without modifying the core files, ensuring your customizations stay intact when updating WordPress.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In this blog, we will be using the <code>nav_menu_css_class</code> filter hook to add the \"active\" class to the menu items. This filter allows us to modify the CSS classes assigned to menu items, so when the current page matches a menu item, we can add the \"active\" class to it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>How WordPress Menus Work</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>WordPress uses a built-in function to generate menus, which are based on <strong>custom menus</strong> defined by the user. The menus are output using the <code>wp_nav_menu()</code> function, and this function automatically adds specific classes to menu items, such as <code>menu-item</code>, <code>menu-item-type-post_type</code>, <code>current-menu-item</code>, etc.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <strong>current-menu-item</strong> class is automatically applied to the active page‚Äôs menu item, meaning that WordPress already detects the active page and adds a class. However, the default WordPress output does not add the Bootstrap-specific \"active\" class.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By using WordPress hooks and filters, you can enhance the existing output by adding the \"active\" class from Bootstrap to the correct menu item, allowing you to use Bootstrap\'s styling and functionality effectively.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The process involves using the <code>nav_menu_css_class</code> filter hook to modify the classes assigned to menu items and checking if a menu item corresponds to the current page or section.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Here‚Äôs a simple solution that will automatically add the \"active\" class to the current menu item:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>add_filter(\'nav_menu_css_class\' , \'special_nav_class\' , 10 , 2);\n\nfunction special_nav_class ($classes, $item) {\nif (in_array(\'current-menu-item\', $classes) ){\n$classes&#91;] = ‚Äòactive ‚Äò;\n}\nreturn $classes;\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-buttons\"><!-- wp:button -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-button\"><a class=\"wp-block-button__link wp-element-button\" href=\"https://codenskills.com/how-to-convert-html-bootstrap-menu-in-wordpress/\">How To Convert Bootstrap Menu In WordPress</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'How to add active class in  WordPress bootstrap menu using hook', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'how-to-add-active-class-in-wordpress-bootstrap-menu-using-hook', '', '', '2025-02-06 14:06:43', '2025-02-06 14:06:43', '', 0, 'https://mycodingsolution.com/?p=72', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(74, 2, '2020-06-27 10:07:45', '2020-06-27 10:07:45', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Breadcrumbs are an essential part of website navigation, improving <strong>user experience</strong> and <strong>SEO</strong>. They help users understand their location within your site and make it easier to navigate back to previous pages.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Instead of using a <strong>plugin</strong>, you can create breadcrumbs manually in WordPress by adding a custom function to your theme‚Äôs <code>functions.php</code> file. This guide will walk you through how to implement breadcrumbs in WordPress without a plugin.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Why Use Breadcrumbs?</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before diving into the implementation, let‚Äôs understand why breadcrumbs are beneficial:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li> <strong>Improves User Experience:</strong> Users can quickly navigate back to previous sections.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li> <strong>Boosts SEO:</strong> Search engines like Google use breadcrumbs to understand site structure.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li> <strong>Enhances Click-Through Rate (CTR):</strong> Breadcrumbs appear in search results, making them more appealing.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li> <strong>Reduces Bounce Rate:</strong> Users are encouraged to explore other pages instead of leaving.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 1: Add Breadcrumb Function in <code>functions.php</code></strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To create a custom breadcrumb trail, we need to define a function in the WordPress theme‚Äôs <code>functions.php</code> file.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Add the following code to your <code>functions.php</code> file:</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>function my_breadcrumbs() {\n  \n  $delimiter = \'‚Ä∫\'; // Separator between breadcrumb items\n  $home = \'Home\'; // Label for the home link\n  $currentBefore = \'&lt;li class=\"breadcrumb-item active\" aria-current=\"page\">\';\n  $currentAfter = \'&lt;/li>\';\n  \n  if (!is_home() &amp;&amp; !is_front_page() || is_paged()) {\n    \n    global $post;\n    $homeLink = get_bloginfo(\'url\');\n    echo \'&lt;ul class=\"breadcrumb\">\';\n    echo \'&lt;li class=\"breadcrumb-item\">&lt;a href=\"\' . $homeLink . \'\">\' . $home . \'&lt;/a>&lt;/li> \' . $delimiter . \' \';\n  \n    if (is_category()) {\n      global $wp_query;\n      $cat_obj = $wp_query->get_queried_object();\n      $thisCat = $cat_obj->term_id;\n      $thisCat = get_category($thisCat);\n      $parentCat = get_category($thisCat->parent);\n      if ($thisCat->parent != 0) echo(get_category_parents($parentCat, TRUE, \' \' . $delimiter . \' \'));\n      echo $currentBefore . single_cat_title(\'\', false) . $currentAfter;\n  \n    } elseif (is_single()) {\n      $cat = get_the_category();\n      $cat = $cat&#91;0];\n      echo \'&lt;li class=\"breadcrumb-item\">&lt;a href=\"\' . get_category_link($cat) . \'\">\' . $cat->name . \'&lt;/a>&lt;/li> \' . $delimiter . \' \';\n      echo $currentBefore . get_the_title() . $currentAfter;\n  \n    } elseif (is_page() &amp;&amp; !$post->post_parent) {\n      echo $currentBefore . get_the_title() . $currentAfter;\n  \n    } elseif (is_page() &amp;&amp; $post->post_parent) {\n      $parent_id = $post->post_parent;\n      $breadcrumbs = array();\n      while ($parent_id) {\n        $page = get_page($parent_id);\n        $breadcrumbs&#91;] = \'&lt;li class=\"breadcrumb-item\">&lt;a href=\"\' . get_permalink($page->ID) . \'\">\' . get_the_title($page->ID) . \'&lt;/a>&lt;/li>\';\n        $parent_id = $page->post_parent;\n      }\n      $breadcrumbs = array_reverse($breadcrumbs);\n      foreach ($breadcrumbs as $crumb) echo $crumb . \' \' . $delimiter . \' \';\n      echo $currentBefore . get_the_title() . $currentAfter;\n  \n    } elseif (is_search()) {\n      echo $currentBefore . \'Search results for \"\' . get_search_query() . \'\"\' . $currentAfter;\n  \n    } elseif (is_404()) {\n      echo $currentBefore . \'Error 404\' . $currentAfter;\n    }\n  \n    echo \'&lt;/ul>\';\n  }\n}\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 2: Call the Breadcrumb Function in <code>header.php</code></strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now that we have defined the breadcrumb function, we need to display it in the correct location on our WordPress site.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Place this code in <code>header.php</code> where you want the breadcrumbs to appear:</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;?php if (function_exists(\'my_breadcrumbs\')) my_breadcrumbs(); ?>\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This ensures that the breadcrumb navigation appears <strong>below the header</strong> or wherever you place this code.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 3: Style the Breadcrumbs with CSS</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To ensure the breadcrumbs match your site‚Äôs design, add the following CSS to your theme‚Äôs <code>style.css</code> file:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>.breadcrumb {\n  list-style: none;\n  padding: 10px 0;\n  background: #f8f9fa;\n  border-radius: 5px;\n  display: flex;\n  gap: 5px;\n}\n\n.breadcrumb li {\n  display: inline;\n  font-size: 14px;\n}\n\n.breadcrumb li a {\n  text-decoration: none;\n  color: #007bff;\n}\n\n.breadcrumb li a:hover {\n  text-decoration: underline;\n}\n\n.breadcrumb-item.active {\n  font-weight: bold;\n  color: #333;\n}\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>his CSS:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Styles the breadcrumb background.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Adds spacing between breadcrumb items.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Highlights the current page in <strong>bold</strong>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 4: Test the Breadcrumb Functionality</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To ensure everything works correctly, visit different pages on your WordPress site, such as:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li> <strong>Homepage:</strong> Breadcrumbs should not appear.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li> <strong>Category Page:</strong> Should show ‚ÄúHome ‚Ä∫ Category Name.‚Äù</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li> <strong>Single Post:</strong> Should show ‚ÄúHome ‚Ä∫ Category ‚Ä∫ Post Title.‚Äù</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li> <strong>Page with Parent:</strong> Should show ‚ÄúHome ‚Ä∫ Parent Page ‚Ä∫ Current Page.‚Äù</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li> <strong>Search Results:</strong> Should display ‚ÄúHome ‚Ä∫ Search results for: keyword.‚Äù</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li> <strong>404 Page:</strong> Should display ‚ÄúHome ‚Ä∫ Error 404.‚Äù</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 5: Enhance Breadcrumb Functionality (Optional)</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To further improve the breadcrumbs, you can:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>1. Add Breadcrumbs to Yoast SEO (Without a Plugin)</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you are using <strong>Yoast SEO</strong>, you can integrate its built-in breadcrumb function:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;?php if ( function_exists(\'yoast_breadcrumb\') ) {\n  yoast_breadcrumb(\'&lt;ul class=\"breadcrumb\">\', \'&lt;/ul>\');\n} ?></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>2. Add Schema Markup for SEO</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To make breadcrumbs <strong>SEO-friendly</strong>, add Schema.org markup:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>echo \'&lt;ul class=\"breadcrumb\" itemscope itemtype=\"https://schema.org/BreadcrumbList\">\';\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Each breadcrumb item should be wrapped in:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;li itemprop=\"itemListElement\" itemscope itemtype=\"https://schema.org/ListItem\">\n  &lt;a itemprop=\"item\" href=\"your-url\">\n    &lt;span itemprop=\"name\">Your Page Name&lt;/span>\n  &lt;/a>\n  &lt;meta itemprop=\"position\" content=\"1\" />\n&lt;/li>\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This helps Google display breadcrumbs in search results.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Adding <strong>breadcrumbs without a plugin</strong> in WordPress is an effective way to improve <strong>navigation, user experience, and SEO</strong>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-buttons\"><!-- wp:button -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-button\"><a class=\"wp-block-button__link wp-element-button\" href=\"https://codenskills.com/how-to-convert-html-bootstrap-menu-in-wordpress/\">How to add active class in WordPress bootstrap menu using hook</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons -->', 'How to add breadcrumb in wordpress without plugin', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'how-to-add-breadcrumb-in-wordpress-without-plugin', '', '', '2025-03-03 09:38:33', '2025-03-03 09:38:33', '', 0, 'https://mycodingsolution.com/?p=74', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(85, 2, '2020-06-27 10:19:14', '2020-06-27 10:19:14', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In WordPress, retrieving the featured image (also known as the post thumbnail) is an essential part of displaying content. By default, WordPress stores the featured image (thumbnail) URL in the database as a post meta value. If you\'re working with custom queries, custom themes, or building your own solutions, there are times when you may need to retrieve the thumbnail URL of a post directly via SQL queries. This blog will walk you through the process of extracting the post thumbnail URL using SQL queries, allowing you to efficiently retrieve image data without relying on WordPress functions.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Understanding WordPress Post Thumbnails</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before diving into the SQL query, let‚Äôs take a moment to understand what a post thumbnail is and how it is stored in WordPress.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>What is a Post Thumbnail?</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A <strong>post thumbnail</strong> in WordPress is essentially the featured image of a post or page. It is commonly used to represent the content visually on the front end of the website. The post thumbnail can appear in places like:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Blog post listings</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Homepages</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Category pages</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Archives</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Widgets</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>And more</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This image is usually selected from the WordPress editor when creating or editing a post. By default, WordPress stores the thumbnail\'s ID in a post‚Äôs metadata (<code>_thumbnail_id</code>), and the actual image‚Äôs path can be retrieved by accessing the relevant post meta.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>How WordPress Stores Post Thumbnails in the Database</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>WordPress stores a variety of metadata related to posts in a set of tables within the database. The main tables that are relevant for post thumbnails are:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>wp_posts</strong>: This table contains information about the posts, including post title, content, and status.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>wp_postmeta</strong>: This table contains the metadata for posts, including the thumbnail ID (stored as <code>_thumbnail_id</code>).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>wp_term_relationships</strong>: This table is used to link posts to categories, tags, or custom taxonomies.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>wp_terms</strong>: This table stores the actual terms (categories or tags) that posts belong to.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To retrieve a post‚Äôs thumbnail, we primarily need to access the <strong><code>_thumbnail_id</code></strong> meta key in the <code>wp_postmeta</code> table, which stores the attachment ID of the image. Then, we need to use this ID to retrieve the image file path, typically stored in the <code>wp_postmeta</code> table with the key <code>_wp_attached_file</code>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Building the SQL Query to Get the Post Thumbnail URL</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now, let‚Äôs dive into the SQL query that will allow you to retrieve the post thumbnail URL directly from the database. WordPress uses multiple tables to store post information, including post metadata, which we can leverage to get the image URL.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>The SQL Query Breakdown</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Below is a detailed SQL query to retrieve the post thumbnail URL along with other post-related data:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>SELECT \n    post.ID,\n    post.post_title,\n    post.post_content,\n    post.post_date,\n    post.category_name,\n    post.category_slug,\n    post.category_id,\n    CONCAT( \'https://mycodingsolution.com/wp-content/uploads/\', thumb.meta_value) AS thumbnail,\n    post.post_type\nFROM (\n    SELECT  \n        p.ID,\n        p.post_content,\n        p.post_title, \n        p.post_date,\n        p.post_type,\n        MAX(CASE WHEN pm.meta_key = \'_thumbnail_id\' THEN pm.meta_value ELSE NULL END) AS thumbnail_id,\n        term.name AS category_name,\n        term.slug AS category_slug,\n        term.term_id AS category_id\n    FROM wp_posts AS p \n    LEFT JOIN wp_postmeta AS pm ON (pm.post_id = p.ID)\n    LEFT JOIN wp_term_relationships AS tr ON tr.object_id = p.ID\n    LEFT JOIN wp_terms AS term ON tr.term_taxonomy_id = term.term_id\n    WHERE p.post_status = \'publish\'\n    GROUP BY p.ID \n    ORDER BY p.post_date DESC\n) AS post\nLEFT JOIN wp_postmeta AS thumb \n    ON thumb.meta_key = \'_wp_attached_file\' \n    AND thumb.post_id = post.thumbnail_id\nORDER BY post.post_date DESC \nLIMIT 3;</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Understanding the Query\'s Output</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The output of this SQL query will return the following columns for each post:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>ID</strong>: The ID of the post.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>post_title</strong>: The title of the post.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>post_content</strong>: The content of the post.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>post_date</strong>: The date when the post was published.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>category_name</strong>: The name of the category the post belongs to.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>category_slug</strong>: The URL-friendly version of the category name.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>category_id</strong>: The ID of the category the post belongs to.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>thumbnail</strong>: The URL of the post‚Äôs thumbnail image.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>post_type</strong>: The type of post (e.g., post, page, custom post type).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This will provide you with all the necessary information, including the URL of the featured image for each post. In 2025, we <span style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px; padding: 0px;\">can</span> all experience more powerful and flexible¬†<a href=\"https://www.dedicatedcore.com/vps-hosting-uk/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" title=\"\">Next-gen VPS</a>¬†hosting, which can offer reliable virtual private server options.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Advantages of Using SQL Queries to Retrieve Thumbnail URLs</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While WordPress provides functions like <code>get_the_post_thumbnail_url()</code> to retrieve thumbnail URLs, there are certain scenarios where executing custom SQL queries directly on the database can be advantageous:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Custom Queries</strong>: When you need to retrieve multiple pieces of information from the database and want to customize your query, SQL queries provide more flexibility and control.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Performance</strong>: Direct SQL queries can be faster in certain situations as they bypass the overhead of WordPress functions, especially if you need to retrieve large sets of data in a custom format.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Advanced Customization</strong>: If you have specific needs that cannot be easily achieved with WordPress functions, raw SQL queries give you the power to craft highly customized solutions.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Conclusion</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Retrieving the post thumbnail URL using SQL queries in WordPress can be a powerful technique for customizing your site and improving performance. By understanding how WordPress stores thumbnails in its database and using SQL to access the data, you can create dynamic and optimized queries tailored to your site‚Äôs needs.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whether you are building a custom theme, plugin, or a unique project, this method offers a direct and efficient approach to obtaining the featured image URL of posts without relying solely on WordPress‚Äôs built-in functions.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By utilizing SQL, you gain complete control over how you retrieve and present the thumbnail URLs, making it a versatile solution for advanced WordPress development.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Note: Please note that using SQL queries directly can be risky and it\'s recommended to use WordPress functions and APIs instead for better security and compatibility.</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-buttons\"><!-- wp:button -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-button\"><a class=\"wp-block-button__link wp-element-button\" href=\"https://codenskills.com/how-to-add-breadcrumb-in-wordpress-without-plugin/\">How to add breadcrumb in WordPress without plugin</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons -->', 'How to get post thumbnail URL by SQL query in WordPress', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'how-to-get-post-thumbnail-url-by-sql-query-in-wordpress', '', '', '2025-04-18 15:35:07', '2025-04-18 10:05:07', '', 0, 'https://mycodingsolution.com/?p=85', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(107, 2, '2020-07-19 03:07:59', '2020-07-19 03:07:59', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To add a custom class to the input field on the WooCommerce checkout page, you can use the <code>woocommerce_checkout_fields</code> filter hook. Here\'s an example code snippet that you can add to your theme\'s <code>functions.php</code> file:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>function custom_checkout_fields( $fields ) {\r\n    $fields&#91;\'billing\']&#91;\'billing_first_name\']&#91;\'class\'] = array( \'custom-class\' );\r\n    return $fields;\r\n}\r\nadd_filter( \'woocommerce_checkout_fields\', \'custom_checkout_fields\' );\r</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This code adds a custom class <code>custom-class</code> to the billing first name field on the checkout page. You can modify this code to add a custom class to any other input field by changing the field key and class name.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once you have added this code, the custom class will be applied to the input field on the checkout page. You can then use CSS to style the input field based on the custom class.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Also, you can use the `woocommerce_form_field_args` filter to add a class. Use the following code.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>add_filter(\'woocommerce_form_field_args\',  \'wc_form_field_args\',10,3);\n  function wc_form_field_args($args, $key, $value) {\n  $args&#91;\'input_class\'] = array( \'form-control\' );\n  return $args;\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-buttons\"><!-- wp:button -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-button\"><a class=\"wp-block-button__link wp-element-button\" href=\"https://codenskills.com/how-to-get-post-thumbnail-url-by-sql-query-in-wordpress/\">How to get post thumbnail url by sql query in WordPress</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons -->', 'Checkout page input and add class in woo-commerce via hooks', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'checkout-page-input-and-add-class-in-woo-commerce-via-hooks', '', '', '2025-03-21 10:52:50', '2025-03-21 10:52:50', '', 0, 'https://mycodingsolution.com/?p=107', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(117, 2, '2020-08-03 15:02:30', '2020-08-03 15:02:30', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To get duplicate values from a table in SQL, you can use the <code>GROUP BY</code> clause with the <code>HAVING</code> clause. Here\'s an example SQL query that retrieves duplicate values from a table named <code>tbl_app_users </code>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>SELECT email, COUNT(*) c FROM tbl_app_users GROUP BY email HAVING c &gt; 1 </code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Replace <code>column_name</code> with the name of the column that you want to check for duplicates. This SQL query groups the rows by the specified column and counts the number of occurrences of each value. The <code>HAVING</code> clause filters the results to show only the values that have more than one occurrence, indicating that they are duplicates.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can modify this SQL query to suit your needs by changing the table name, column name, and any additional conditions that you want to apply.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-buttons\"><!-- wp:button -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-button\"><a class=\"wp-block-button__link wp-element-button\" href=\"https://codenskills.com/checkout-page-input-and-add-class-in-woo-commerce-via-hooks/\">Checkout page input and add class in woo-commerce via hooks</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons -->', 'How to Find Duplicate Values in SQL', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'sql-query-to-get-duplicate-value', '', '', '2025-03-21 11:03:36', '2025-03-21 11:03:36', '', 0, 'https://mycodingsolution.com/?p=117', 0, 'post', '', 0);
