(408, 1, '2023-03-03 09:28:40', '2023-03-03 09:28:40', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To clear the cache in Laravel using CLI, you can use the <code>php artisan cache:clear</code> command. This command clears the application cache, including the cache of compiled views, routes, and configuration files.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here are the steps to clear the cache in Laravel using CLI:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Open the command prompt or terminal on your computer.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Navigate to the root directory of your Laravel application.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Run the following command:</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Wait for the command to finish executing. Once it is done, you should see a message confirming that the cache has been cleared.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>php artisan cache:clear\r</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can also clear specific caches using CLI, such as the view cache, route cache, and config cache, by running the following commands:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>php artisan view:clear\r\nphp artisan route:clear\r\nphp artisan config:clear</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By clearing the cache, you can ensure that your Laravel application runs smoothly and that any changes you make to the code are reflected immediately.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-buttons\"><!-- wp:button -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-button\"><a class=\"wp-block-button__link wp-element-button\" href=\"https://codenskills.com/how-to-change-single-product-page-title/\">How To Change Single Product Page Title</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons -->', 'How TO Clear Chache in Laravel By CLI', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '152-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-03-03 09:28:40', '2023-03-03 09:28:40', '', 152, 'https://codenskills.com/?p=408', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(410, 1, '2023-03-03 09:34:12', '2023-03-03 09:34:12', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can redirect a URL permanently (301 redirects) using .htaccess the file. To create a 301 redirect, you need to add a redirect rule in the <code>.htaccess</code> file.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here is an example of how to redirect <code>old-url</code> to <code>new-url</code> using <code>.htaccess</code>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>Redirect 301 /old-url /new-url\r</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the above code, <code>old-url</code> is the URL you want to redirect, and <code>new-url</code> is the URL where you want to redirect. The <code>301</code> indicates that the redirection is permanent, which will update search engines and browsers with the new URL.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can add multiple redirect rules in <code>.htaccess</code> file for multiple URLs that you want to redirect.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Additionally, you can also use regular expressions in <code>.htaccess</code> file to redirect URLs based on patterns. This is useful if you want to redirect multiple URLs that match a particular pattern.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here is an example of how to redirect URLs based on a pattern:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>RewriteEngine On\r\nRewriteRule ^old-url(.*)$ /new-url$1 &#91;R=301,L]\r</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>RewriteEngine On\n\nRewriteCond %{HTTPS} off \nRewriteRule ^(.*)$ https://%{HTTP_HOST}%{REQUEST_URI} &#91;L,R=301]\nRewriteCond %{HTTP_HOST} ^www\\.(.*)$ &#91;NC]\nRewriteRule ^(.*)$ https://%1%{REQUEST_URI} &#91;R=301,QSA,NC,L]</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->', 'How To Redirect 301 URL by .htaccess', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '154-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-03-03 09:34:12', '2023-03-03 09:34:12', '', 154, 'https://codenskills.com/?p=410', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(411, 1, '2023-03-03 09:34:26', '2023-03-03 09:34:26', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can redirect a URL permanently (301 redirects) using .htaccess the file. To create a 301 redirect, you need to add a redirect rule in the <code>.htaccess</code> file.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here is an example of how to redirect <code>old-url</code> to <code>new-url</code> using <code>.htaccess</code>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>Redirect 301 /old-url /new-url\r</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the above code, <code>old-url</code> is the URL you want to redirect, and <code>new-url</code> is the URL where you want to redirect. The <code>301</code> indicates that the redirection is permanent, which will update search engines and browsers with the new URL.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can add multiple redirect rules in <code>.htaccess</code> file for multiple URLs that you want to redirect.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Additionally, you can also use regular expressions in <code>.htaccess</code> file to redirect URLs based on patterns. This is useful if you want to redirect multiple URLs that match a particular pattern.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here is an example of how to redirect URLs based on a pattern:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>RewriteEngine On\r\nRewriteRule ^old-url(.*)$ /new-url$1 &#91;R=301,L]\r</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>RewriteEngine On\n\nRewriteCond %{HTTPS} off \nRewriteRule ^(.*)$ https://%{HTTP_HOST}%{REQUEST_URI} &#91;L,R=301]\nRewriteCond %{HTTP_HOST} ^www\\.(.*)$ &#91;NC]\nRewriteRule ^(.*)$ https://%1%{REQUEST_URI} &#91;R=301,QSA,NC,L]</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the above code, <code>^old-url(.*)$</code> is the pattern for the URLs you want to redirect, and <code>/new-url$1</code> is the URL where you want to redirect. <code>$1</code> is a back-reference to the matched pattern, which allows you to preserve any additional URL path information that follows <code>old-url</code>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Make sure to backup your <code>.htaccess</code> file before making any changes and test the redirect thoroughly to ensure it works as expected.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'How To Redirect 301 URL by .htaccess', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '154-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-03-03 09:34:26', '2023-03-03 09:34:26', '', 154, 'https://codenskills.com/?p=411', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
