(467, 1, '2023-04-03 12:20:44', '2023-04-03 12:20:44', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Laravel is a popular PHP web application framework that provides a set of useful features and tools for developing modern web applications. Here are some of the most commonly used Laravel commands:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><code><strong>php artisan serve</strong></code> - Starts a development server to serve your Laravel application on your local machine.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><code><strong>php artisan make:model</strong> ModelName</code> - Creates a new model class in the <code>app/Models</code> directory.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><code><strong>php artisan make:controller</strong> ControllerName</code> - Creates a new controller class in the <code>app/Http/Controllers</code> directory.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><code><strong>php artisan make:migration</strong> create_table_name</code> - Creates a new database migration file in the <code>database/migrations</code> directory.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><code><strong>php artisan migrate</strong></code> - Runs all pending database migrations.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><code><strong>php artisan tinker</strong></code> - Opens the Laravel REPL (Read-Eval-Print Loop) which allows you to interact with your Laravel application\'s code and data in real-time.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><code><strong>php artisan make:middleware</strong> MiddlewareName</code> - Creates a new middleware class in the <code>app/Http/Middleware</code> directory.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><code><strong>php artisan make:auth</strong></code> - Generates basic login and registration views and controllers for authentication.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><code>php artisan route:list</code> </strong>- Lists all the registered routes for your Laravel application.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><code>php artisan optimize</code> -</strong> Optimizes the application by generating a compiled class file to speed up the application\'s performance.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><code>php artisan view:cache</code> - </strong>This command is used to cache all of your application\'s views, which can help to improve the loading time of your web pages. Once the views are cached, Laravel will use the cached versions instead of compiling them from the source files on each request.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><code>php artisan config:cache</code> -</strong> This command is used to cache all of your application\'s configuration files, which can help to improve the overall performance of your application by reducing the time it takes to load configuration values. Once the configuration files are cached, Laravel will use the cached versions instead of loading them from disk on each request.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><code>php artisan route:cache</code> -</strong> This command is used to cache all of your application\'s routes, which can help to improve the performance of your application by reducing the time it takes to match incoming requests to the appropriate route. Once the routes are cached, Laravel will use the cached versions instead of loading them from disk on each request.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><code><strong>php artisan optimize:clear</strong></code> command, Laravel will remove the compiled class file, and your application will revert to using the original class files, which will be loaded individually on each request. This can lead to slightly slower application performance, but it may be necessary in some situations to ensure that your application is running correctly.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>the <strong><code>sudo chmod -R 777 bootstrap/cache</code> </strong>and <code><strong>sudo chmod -R 777 storage</strong></code> commands, you are setting the permissions of these directories and all their contents to <code>777</code>, which means that all users and groups on the system will have full access to these directories and their contents.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><code><strong>php artisan key:generate</strong></code> is a command used to generate a new application key in Laravel. The application key is a random string of characters used to encrypt data in your application, such as user sessions and authentication cookies. Running this command will generate a new key and update the <code>APP_KEY</code> value in your <code>.env</code> file.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><code><strong>php artisan storage:link</strong></code> is a command used to create a symbolic link between the <code>public</code> directory and the <code>storage/app/public</code> directory in Laravel. This allows you to easily serve files stored in the <code>storage/app/public</code> directory through a URL, such as uploaded images or files. Once you run this command, files stored in the <code>storage/app/public</code> directory can be accessed through a URL like <code>http://your-app.com/storage/filename.ext</code>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><code>php artisan migrate:refresh --seed</code> </strong>is a command used to refresh the database migration and seed it with initial data in Laravel. Running this command will drop all tables in the database and then re-run all migrations and seed the database with initial data. This command is useful during development when you need to reset your database to its initial state.<strong>Keep in mind that running php artisan migrate:refresh --seed will delete all data in your database, so you should only use it during development and testing, not in a production environment. Additionally, before running this command, make sure you have a backup of your database to avoid losing any important data.</strong></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>php artisan serve \nphp artisan make:model ModelName \nphp artisan make:controller ControllerName \nphp artisan make:migration create_table_name \nphp artisan migrate \nphp artisan tinker \nphp artisan make:middleware MiddlewareName\nphp artisan make:auth \nphp artisan route:list \nphp artisan optimize \nphp artisan view:cache \nphp artisan config:cache \nphp artisan route:cache \nphp artisan optimize:clear \nsudo chmod -R 777 bootstrap/cache and sudo chmod -R 777 storage \nphp artisan key:generate \nphp artisan storage:link \nphp artisan migrate:refresh --seed </code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>These are just a few examples of the many commands available in Laravel. Each command is designed to simplify common development tasks and increase developer productivity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Must-Know Laravel Commands for Developers (Boost Productivity & Efficiency)', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'must-know-laravel-commands-for-developers-boost-productivity-efficiency', '', '', '2025-03-21 11:09:20', '2025-03-21 11:09:20', '', 0, 'https://codenskills.com/?p=467', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(468, 1, '2023-03-31 20:07:43', '2023-03-31 20:07:43', '<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>php artisan view:cache\nphp artisan config:cache\nphp artisan route:cache\n\nphp artisan optimize:clear\n\nsudo chmod -R 777 bootstrap/cache\nsudo chmod -R 777 storage\n\n\nphp artisan key:generate\nphp artisan storage:link\n\n\nphp artisan migrate:refresh --seed\n\n\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->', 'aaa', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '467-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-03-31 20:07:43', '2023-03-31 20:07:43', '', 467, 'https://codenskills.com/?p=468', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(469, 1, '2023-04-01 04:47:59', '2023-04-01 04:47:59', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To make a dynamic HTML sitemap in a Shopify template, you can follow these steps:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Open the Shopify theme editor and select the template where you want to add the sitemap.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Create a new page by clicking on the \"Add page\" button in the Pages section of the Shopify admin.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Give the page a name like \"Sitemap\" or \"Site Map\".</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>In the theme editor, open the \"Add section\" tab and select the \"Rich text\" section.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>In the rich text section, add the following HTML code to create a dynamic sitemap:</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>page.sitemap.liquid\n\n\n&lt;a name=\"pagecontent\" id=\"pagecontent\"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;\n\n&lt;div class=\"sixteen columns page clearfix\"&gt;\n  &lt;h1&gt;\n    {{ page.title }}\n  &lt;/h1&gt;\n \n     \n   \n     \n    &lt;h2&gt;Collections&lt;/h2&gt;\n    &lt;ul &gt;\n    {% for c in collections %}\n    &lt;li&gt;\n    &lt;a href=\"{{ c.url }}\"&gt;{{ c.title }}&lt;/a&gt;\n    &lt;/li&gt;\n    {% endfor %}\n    &lt;/ul&gt;\n    &lt;h2&gt;Products&lt;/h2&gt;\n    &lt;ul&gt;\n    {% for product in collections.all.products %}\n    &lt;li&gt;\n    &lt;a href=\"{{ product.url }}\"&gt;{{ product.title }}&lt;/a&gt;\n    &lt;/li&gt;\n    {% endfor %}\n    &lt;/ul&gt;\n   &lt;h2&gt;Pages&lt;/h2&gt;\n     &lt;ul&gt;\n{%- paginate pages by 50 -%}\n    {%- for p in pages -%}\n        &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=\"{{ p.url }}\"&gt;{{ p.title }}&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;\n    {%- endfor -%}\n   \n{%- endpaginate -%}\n&lt;/ul&gt;\n\n&lt;/div&gt;</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This code uses a for loop to iterate over the links in the \"main-menu\" link list and generates a list of links with their titles and URLs.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"start\":6} -->\n<ol start=\"6\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Save the changes to the section and preview the page to see the dynamic sitemap in action.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Note: If you want to customize the sitemap further, you can modify the HTML code to include additional link lists or styling.</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-buttons\"><!-- wp:button -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-button\"><a class=\"wp-block-button__link wp-element-button\" href=\"\">Check if links are external with jQuery/javascript.</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons -->', 'How To Make Dynamic HTML Sitemap in Shopify', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '443-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-04-01 04:47:59', '2023-04-01 04:47:59', '', 443, 'https://codenskills.com/?p=469', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(470, 1, '2023-04-01 04:48:22', '2023-04-01 04:48:22', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To make a dynamic HTML sitemap in a Shopify template, you can follow these steps:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Open the Shopify theme editor and select the template where you want to add the sitemap.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Create a new page by clicking on the \"Add page\" button in the Pages section of the Shopify admin.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Give the page a name like \"Sitemap\" or \"Site Map\".</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>In the theme editor, open the \"Add section\" tab and select the \"Rich text\" section.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>In the rich text section, add the following HTML code to create a dynamic sitemap:</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>page.sitemap.liquid\n\n\n&lt;a name=\"pagecontent\" id=\"pagecontent\"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;\n\n&lt;div class=\"sixteen columns page clearfix\"&gt;\n  &lt;h1&gt;\n    {{ page.title }}\n  &lt;/h1&gt;\n \n     \n   \n     \n    &lt;h2&gt;Collections&lt;/h2&gt;\n    &lt;ul &gt;\n    {% for c in collections %}\n    &lt;li&gt;\n    &lt;a href=\"{{ c.url }}\"&gt;{{ c.title }}&lt;/a&gt;\n    &lt;/li&gt;\n    {% endfor %}\n    &lt;/ul&gt;\n    &lt;h2&gt;Products&lt;/h2&gt;\n    &lt;ul&gt;\n    {% for product in collections.all.products %}\n    &lt;li&gt;\n    &lt;a href=\"{{ product.url }}\"&gt;{{ product.title }}&lt;/a&gt;\n    &lt;/li&gt;\n    {% endfor %}\n    &lt;/ul&gt;\n   &lt;h2&gt;Pages&lt;/h2&gt;\n     &lt;ul&gt;\n{%- paginate pages by 50 -%}\n    {%- for p in pages -%}\n        &lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=\"{{ p.url }}\"&gt;{{ p.title }}&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;\n    {%- endfor -%}\n   \n{%- endpaginate -%}\n&lt;/ul&gt;\n\n&lt;/div&gt;</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This code uses a for loop to iterate over the links in the \"main-menu\" link list and generates a list of links with their titles and URLs.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"start\":6} -->\n<ol start=\"6\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Save the changes to the section and preview the page to see the dynamic sitemap in action.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Note: If you want to customize the sitemap further, you can modify the HTML code to include additional link lists or styling.</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-buttons\"><!-- wp:button -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-button\"><a class=\"wp-block-button__link wp-element-button\" href=\"https://codenskills.com/check-if-links-are-external-with-jquery-javascript/\">Check if links are external with jQuery/javascript.</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons -->', 'How To Make Dynamic HTML Sitemap in Shopify', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '443-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-04-01 04:48:22', '2023-04-01 04:48:22', '', 443, 'https://codenskills.com/?p=470', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(471, 1, '2023-04-01 04:49:11', '2023-04-01 04:49:11', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you want to add an email recipient for order notification emails in WooCommerce, you can use the following code:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>add_filter( \'woocommerce_email_recipient_new_order\', \'add_new_order_email_recipient\', 10, 2 );\n\nfunction add_new_order_email_recipient( $recipient, $order ) {\n    $recipient .= \', email@example.com\'; // Replace \"email@example.com\" with the email address you want to add\n    return $recipient;\n}\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This code adds an email address to the recipient list for the \"New Order\" notification email in WooCommerce. You can replace \"<a href=\"mailto:email@example.com\">email@example.com</a>\" with the email address you want to add. If you want to add multiple email addresses, separate them with a comma.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can add this code to your theme\'s functions.php file or a custom plugin.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By adding an email recipient for order notification emails in WooCommerce, you can ensure that the right people are notified when an order is placed on your site.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>add_filter( \'woocommerce_email_recipient_new_order\', \'new_order_additional_recipients\', 20, 2 );<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>function new_order_additional_recipients( $recipient, $order ) {\nif ( ! is_a( $order, \'WC_Order\' ) ) return $recipient;\n// Set Below your email adresses\n$email1 = \'name1@domain.com\';\n$email2 = \'name2@domain.com\';\n\n// Get the shipping method Id\n$shipping_items = $order-&gt;get_items(\'shipping\');\n$shipping_item  = reset($shipping_items);\n$shipping_method_id  = $shipping_item-&gt;get_method_id() . \':\';\n$shipping_method_id .= $shipping_item-&gt;get_instance_id();\n\n// Adding recipients conditionally\nif ( \'flat_rate:8\' == $shipping_method_id )\n    $recipient .= \',\' . $email1;\nelseif ( \'flat_rate:9\' == $shipping_method_id )\n    $recipient .= \',\' . $email2;\n\nreturn $recipient;\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-buttons\"><!-- wp:button -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-button\"><a class=\"wp-block-button__link wp-element-button\" href=\"https://codenskills.com/check-if-links-are-external-with-jquery-javascript/\">Check if links are external with jQuery/javascript.</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons -->', 'How to add Email Recipient Add Woo Commerce', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '137-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-04-01 04:49:11', '2023-04-01 04:49:11', '', 137, 'https://codenskills.com/?p=471', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(472, 1, '2023-04-01 04:50:25', '2023-04-01 04:50:25', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before making any changes to your website\'s database, it\'s important to make a backup in case anything goes wrong. Once you\'ve made a backup, you can follow these steps to change your WordPress URL from HTTP to HTTPS from the database:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Log in to your hosting account and navigate to the cPanel dashboard.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Open phpMyAdmin and select your WordPress database from the left-hand menu.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Click on the \"wp_options\" table and look for the \"siteurl\" and \"home\" rows.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Edit both rows by clicking the pencil icon to the left of the row.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Change the \"option_value\" field for both rows to your new HTTPS URL, and click the \"Go\" button to save the changes.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Verify that the changes have been made by accessing your WordPress site\'s URL with HTTPS.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When we update the database content links without using the plugin then many problems are generated if we update the query without taking a backup. In MySQL database, we have to use the following SQL query for a different table.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>UPDATE wp_options SET option_value = replace(option_value, \'http://codenskills.com\', \'https://codenskills.com\') WHERE option_name = \'home\' OR option_name = \'siteurl\';\n\nUPDATE wp_postmeta SET meta_value = replace(meta_value,\'http://codenskills.com\',\'https://codenskills.com\');\nUPDATE wp_posts SET guid = replace(guid, \'http://codenskills.com\',\'https://codenskills.com\');\n\nUPDATE wp_posts SET post_content = replace(post_content, \'http://codenskills.com\',\'https://codenskills.com\');\n\nUPDATE wp_posts SET pinged = REPLACE(pinged, \'http://codenskills.com\', \'https://codenskills.com\')WHERE pinged LIKE \'%http://codenskills.com%\';\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>if the WordPress page has been made by <strong>WP page-bakery</strong> or <strong>editor </strong>then the following query must be run </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>\nUPDATE wp_posts SET post_content = REPLACE(post_content, \'src=\"http://codenskills.com\', \'src=\"https://codenskills.com\')WHERE post_content LIKE \'%src=\"http://codenskills.com%\';\n\nUPDATE wp_posts SET post_content = REPLACE(post_content, \"src=\'http://codenskills.com\", \"src=\'https://codenskills.com\")WHERE post_content LIKE \"%src=\'http://codenskills.com%\";\n\nUPDATE wp_posts SET post_content = REPLACE(post_content, \'href=\"http://codenskills.com\', \'href=\"https://codenskills.com\')WHERE post_content LIKE \'%href=\"http://codenskills.com%\';\n\nUPDATE wp_posts SET post_content = REPLACE(post_content, \"href=\'http://codenskills.com\", \"href=\'https://codenskills.com\")WHERE post_content LIKE \"%href=\'http://codenskills.com%\";\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-buttons\"><!-- wp:button -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-button\"><a class=\"wp-block-button__link wp-element-button\" href=\"https://codenskills.com/how-to-force-redirect-http-to-https-in-wordpress-via-htaccess/\">How to force redirect HTTP to HTTPS in WordPress via htaccess</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you have any caching plugins or services enabled, it\'s recommended to clear the cache after making changes to the database to ensure that your website displays correctly with the new URL. If you encounter any issues, you can restore the backup you made earlier and try again or seek help from a professional developer.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'How to change WordPress  URL HTTP to HTTPS  from database', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '33-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-04-01 04:50:25', '2023-04-01 04:50:25', '', 33, 'https://codenskills.com/?p=472', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(473, 1, '2023-04-01 04:51:15', '2023-04-01 04:51:15', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When we implemented the bootstrap menu in WordPress.  you may be frustrated with the built-in menu options. There isn‚Äôt an easy way to tell WordPress to swap out the current menu item class with bootstrap‚Äôs active class. there is a given below hook. this following  script write a script in the fucntion.php file</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>add_filter(\'nav_menu_css_class\' , \'special_nav_class\' , 10 , 2);\n\nfunction special_nav_class ($classes, $item) {\nif (in_array(\'current-menu-item\', $classes) ){\n$classes&#91;] = ‚Äòactive ‚Äò;\n}\nreturn $classes;\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-buttons\"><!-- wp:button -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-button\"><a class=\"wp-block-button__link wp-element-button\" href=\"https://codenskills.com/how-to-convert-html-bootstrap-menu-in-wordpress/\">How To Convert Bootstrap Menu In WordPress</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In this example, we are checking if the current menu item has the <code>current-menu-item</code> class, which indicates that it is the current page. If it does, we add the <code>active</code> class to the array of CSS classes for that menu item.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can add this code to your WordPress theme\'s <code>functions.php</code> file to apply the active class to all Bootstrap menus. If you only want to apply the active class to a specific menu, you can modify the code to check for the menu ID or other criteria.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'How to add active class in  WordPress bootstrap menu using hook', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '72-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-04-01 04:51:15', '2023-04-01 04:51:15', '', 72, 'https://codenskills.com/?p=473', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(475, 1, '2023-04-01 04:54:01', '2023-04-01 04:54:01', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>We are going to make WordPress menu int bootstrap menu by walker class. first define class and called walker  following code in function.php file</strong> </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":176,\"width\":823,\"height\":129,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large is-resized\"><img src=\"https://codenskills.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/05/Screenshot_2021-05-27_18_29_48-1024x162.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-176\" width=\"823\" height=\"129\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>class submenu_wrapper extends Walker_Nav_Menu {\n// add classes to ul sub-menus\nfunction start_lvl( &amp;$output, $depth = 0, $args = array() ) {\n// depth dependent classes\n$indent = ( $depth &gt; 0 ? str_repeat( \"\\t\", $depth ) : \'\' ); // code indent\n$display_depth = ( $depth + 1); // because it counts the first submenu as 0\n$classes = array(\n/* \'dropdown-menu left-1\'*/\n\'dropdown-menu\'\n);\n$class_names = implode( \' \', $classes );   \n // build html\n    if ($display_depth == 1) {\n        $output .= \"\\n\" . $indent . \'&lt;ul class=\"\' . $class_names . \'\"&gt;\' . \"\\n\";\n    } else {\n        $output .= \"\\n\" . $indent . \'&lt;ul class=\"\' . $class_names . \'\"&gt;\' . \"\\n\";\n    }\n}\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>After the extending walker class, we will add classes and attribute  in anchor tag  by  \"nav_menu_link_attributes\" Filter. for a you have to use it as per following code.</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>add_filter( \'nav_menu_link_attributes\', \'anchor_menu_add_class\', 10, 4 );    \nfunction anchor_menu_add_class( $atts, $item, $args ,$depth=0) {\n        if ($args-&gt;walker-&gt;has_children==1 &amp;&amp; $depth === 0 ) {\n          $atts&#91;\'href\']          = ! empty( $item-&gt;url ) ? $item-&gt;url : \'\';\n          $atts&#91;\'data-toggle\']   = \'dropdown\';\n          $atts&#91;\'class\']         = \'dropdown-toggle\';\n          $atts&#91;\'aria-haspopup\']    = \'true\';\n          $atts&#91;\'aria-expanded\']=\'false\';\n        } elseif($depth === 0) {\n            $atts&#91;\'href\'] = ! empty( $item-&gt;url ) ? $item-&gt;url : \'\';\n            $atts&#91;\'class\']         = \'\';\n        } elseif($depth === 1) {\n          $atts&#91;\'href\'] = ! empty( $item-&gt;url ) ? $item-&gt;url : \'\';\n          $atts&#91;\'class\']         = \'dropdown-item\';\n        }\n        /*if($depth === 0) {\n            $atts&#91;\'href\'] = ! empty( $item-&gt;url ) ? $item-&gt;url : \'\';\n            $atts&#91;\'class\']         = \'nav-link\';\n        }elseif ($args-&gt;walker-&gt;has_children==1 &amp;&amp; $depth === 0 ) {\n          $atts&#91;\'href\']          = ! empty( $item-&gt;url ) ? $item-&gt;url : \'\';\n          $atts&#91;\'data-toggle\']   = \'dropdown\';\n          $atts&#91;\'class\']         = \'nav-link dropdown-toggle\';\n          $atts&#91;\'aria-haspopup\']    = \'true\';\n          $atts&#91;\'aria-expanded\']=\'false\';\n        } elseif($depth === 1) {\n          $atts&#91;\'href\'] = ! empty( $item-&gt;url ) ? $item-&gt;url : \'\';\n          $atts&#91;\'class\']         = \'dropdown-item\';\n        }*/\n       // print_r($args-&gt;walker-&gt;has_children);\n        //echo \"&lt;pre&gt;\";\n       // print_r($item);\n        //die;\n        return $atts;\n    }</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Calling walker In header.php </strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;?php \necho wp_nav_menu(array(\'menu\'=&gt;\'Home Menu\',\'menu_class\'=&gt;\'navbar-nav ml-auto\',\'walker\'=&gt;new submenu_wrapper,\'container\'=&gt;false)); \n?&gt;</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-buttons\"><!-- wp:button -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-button\"><a class=\"wp-block-button__link wp-element-button\" href=\"https://codenskills.com/how-to-add-active-class-in-wordpress-bootstrap-menu-using-hook/\">Add Active class in wordpress menu by hook </a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons -->', 'How To Convert HTML Bootstrap Menu In WordPress', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '39-revision-v1', '', '', '2023-04-01 04:54:01', '2023-04-01 04:54:01', '', 39, 'https://codenskills.com/?p=475', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
