li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Access to .htaccess File</strong>: The <code>.htaccess</code> file is located in your WordPress installation‚Äôs root directory. You need to have access to this file in order to configure the necessary redirect rules.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Steps to Force HTTP to HTTPS in WordPress via .htaccess</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once you have your SSL certificate and access to the <code>.htaccess</code> file, the next step is to force a redirect from HTTP to HTTPS. Here‚Äôs how you can do it:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">1. <strong>Locate the .htaccess File</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <code>.htaccess</code> file is typically located in the root directory of your WordPress installation. You can access this file via FTP, SFTP, or through the file manager in your web hosting control panel (cPanel, Plesk, etc.).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you don‚Äôt see the <code>.htaccess</code> file, it might be hidden by default. You can enable hidden files in your FTP client or file manager to make it visible.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">2. <strong>Back Up Your .htaccess File</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before making any changes, always back up your <code>.htaccess</code> file. This is a precautionary step in case you make an error, and you need to restore the original file.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">3. <strong>Edit the .htaccess File</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once you‚Äôve located the <code>.htaccess</code> file and made a backup, you can begin editing it. Open the file in a text editor and add the following code to force a redirect from HTTP to HTTPS.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;IfModule mod_rewrite.c>\nRewriteEngine On\nRewriteBase /\n\nRewriteCond %{HTTPS} !=on\nRewriteRule ^ https://%{HTTP_HOST}%{REQUEST_URI} &#91;L,R=301]\n\n# BEGIN WordPress\nRewriteRule ^index\\.php$ - &#91;L]\nRewriteCond %{REQUEST_FILENAME} !-f\nRewriteCond %{REQUEST_FILENAME} !-d\nRewriteRule . /index.php &#91;L]\n&lt;/IfModule></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Explanation of the Code:</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>1. <code>&lt;IfModule mod_rewrite.c&gt;</code></strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This line checks if the <code>mod_rewrite</code> module is enabled on the server. The <code>mod_rewrite</code> module is necessary for URL rewriting (which is how we handle the HTTP to HTTPS redirection).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>2. <code>RewriteEngine On</code></strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This line enables the rewrite engine, which is required for the rewrite rules to take effect.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>3. <code>RewriteBase /</code></strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <code>RewriteBase</code> directive is used to specify the base URL for the rewrites. In most cases, this should be set to <code>/</code>, as it applies to the entire site.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>4. <code>RewriteCond %{HTTPS} !=on</code></strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This line checks if the request is not using HTTPS. The <code>%{HTTPS}</code> variable holds the current connection‚Äôs protocol. If it is not set to \"on\" (meaning the request is using HTTP), the condition evaluates as true, and the next rule is applied.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>5. <code>RewriteRule ^ https://%{HTTP_HOST}%{REQUEST_URI} [L,R=301]</code></strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If the above condition is true (i.e., the request is using HTTP), this rule redirects the user to the HTTPS version of the same URL. The <code>R=301</code> flag signifies that this is a permanent redirect (301), and the <code>L</code> flag tells Apache to stop processing further rules if this rule is matched.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>6. <code># BEGIN WordPress</code></strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This comment marks the beginning of WordPress-specific rewrite rules. WordPress automatically adds its own rewrite rules here, which are responsible for handling permalinks and other URL rewrites.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>7. <code>RewriteRule ^index\\.php$ - [L]</code></strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This rule ensures that any requests for <code>index.php</code> are handled by WordPress and not redirected or rewritten.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>8. <code>RewriteCond %{REQUEST_FILENAME} !-f</code> and <code>RewriteCond %{REQUEST_FILENAME} !-d</code></strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>These conditions check if the requested file or directory exists on the server. If the requested resource is not a valid file or directory, the request will be sent to WordPress‚Äôs <code>index.php</code> file.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>9. <code>RewriteRule . /index.php [L]</code></strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This rule ensures that any requests for non-existent files or directories are routed to WordPress‚Äôs <code>index.php</code> file for processing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">4. <strong>Save the .htaccess File</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once you‚Äôve added the code, save the <code>.htaccess</code> file. After saving, you‚Äôve successfully configured your website to force a redirect from HTTP to HTTPS.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">5. <strong>Test the Redirect</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To ensure that the redirect is working, visit your website using <code>http://</code> and see if you are automatically redirected to the <code>https://</code> version of the page. For example, visit <code>http://www.yoursite.com</code> and check if it redirects to <code>https://www.yoursite.com</code>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If the redirect works as expected, your site is now fully set up to use HTTPS.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Common Issues and Troubleshooting</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While forcing the HTTP to HTTPS redirect via <code>.htaccess</code> is generally straightforward, there are some issues you may encounter. Here are a few common problems and solutions:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">1. <strong>Infinite Redirect Loop</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>An infinite redirect loop can occur if there are conflicting rules in the <code>.htaccess</code> file. Make sure that you don‚Äôt have any other redirect rules that conflict with the ones we added.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">2. <strong>Mixed Content Issues</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you switch to HTTPS, you may encounter mixed content issues, which happen when some resources (like images, scripts, or stylesheets) are still loaded over HTTP. To fix this, you can:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Update your WordPress settings to use <code>https://</code> for the site URL and home URL.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Manually update URLs in your content or database.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Use a plugin like ‚ÄúBetter Search Replace‚Äù to replace all instances of <code>http://</code> with <code>https://</code>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">3. <strong>SSL Certificate Not Installed</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If your SSL certificate is not installed properly, the browser may show a security warning even if the redirect is working. Ensure that your SSL certificate is correctly installed by checking with your hosting provider.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Conclusion</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Forcing a redirect from HTTP to HTTPS in WordPress is a crucial step to ensure the security, SEO, and user confidence of your website. By modifying the <code>.htaccess</code> file, you can easily ensure that all visitors are redirected to the secure HTTPS version of your site. The code we provided is simple to implement and highly effective.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once you‚Äôve made the change, be sure to test it thoroughly and check for any issues such as mixed content. If you encounter any problems, refer to the troubleshooting section to resolve common issues.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By following these steps, you‚Äôll enhance the security of your website, improve its search engine ranking, and provide a better experience for your users.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":6,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img src=\"https://codenskills.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/http-to-https-in-wordpress-by-htaccess.png\" alt=\"how-to-force-redirect-http-to-https-in-wordpress-by-htaccess\" class=\"wp-image-6\" title=\"how-to-force-redirect-http-to-https-in-wordpress-by-htaccess\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Note: Before making changes to your .htaccess file, it\'s recommended to create a backup copy of the file in case anything goes wrong.</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-buttons\"><!-- wp:button -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-button\"><a class=\"wp-block-button__link wp-element-button\">How to change WordPress URL HTTP to HTTPS from database</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons -->', 'How to Force Redirect HTTP to HTTPS in WordPress via .htaccess', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '1-revision-v1', '', '', '2025-02-06 12:00:22', '2025-02-06 12:00:22', '', 1, 'https://codenskills.com/?p=672', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(674, 1, '2025-02-06 12:29:53', '2025-02-06 12:29:53', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In today‚Äôs online world, ensuring the security of your website is paramount. One of the most significant steps in securing your WordPress website is by enabling HTTPS (HyperText Transfer Protocol Secure) instead of the standard HTTP. HTTPS encrypts the communication between the browser and the server, which means all the data exchanged is securely transmitted. This is especially crucial for websites that handle sensitive information, such as user logins, forms, payments, and other personal data.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Migrating a website from HTTP to HTTPS not only improves security but also helps your website perform better in terms of SEO (Search Engine Optimization). Search engines like Google prioritize secure websites and reward them with a ranking boost. Furthermore, users are more likely to trust websites marked with a padlock icon in the browser\'s address bar, signaling that their data is secure.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While switching your WordPress site from HTTP to HTTPS might seem like a complex task, it is actually a straightforward process that can be accomplished in various ways. One of the most effective methods is by directly modifying the WordPress database to reflect the new HTTPS URL. In this blog, we will explain step-by-step how you can change your WordPress URL from HTTP to HTTPS using the database.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Why Move from HTTP to HTTPS?</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before delving into the details of how to change your WordPress URL from HTTP to HTTPS in the database, let‚Äôs first discuss why this migration is essential.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">1. <strong>Improved Security</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you switch from HTTP to HTTPS, data exchanged between the server and the browser is encrypted. This ensures that no sensitive data, such as passwords or credit card information, can be intercepted or tampered with during transmission. For WordPress sites, this is critical, especially for eCommerce websites and login pages.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">2. <strong>SEO Benefits</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Search engines like Google use HTTPS as a ranking signal. Websites that are secured with SSL certificates and use HTTPS generally get a small ranking boost compared to HTTP websites. In 2014, Google made HTTPS a ranking factor, and this has since become more important. Moving to HTTPS ensures your site is more discoverable and has better search engine visibility.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">3. <strong>Trust and User Confidence</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Browsers like Google Chrome display a ‚ÄúNot Secure‚Äù message in the address bar when users visit a site without HTTPS. This can make visitors uncomfortable and hesitant to interact with your site, especially if it requires login details or personal information. HTTPS builds trust with your users, who can see the padlock symbol next to the URL.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\">4. <strong>Compliance and Legal Requirements</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Certain regulatory and legal frameworks require websites to handle data securely. If your site deals with personal user information, it may be required by law to use HTTPS. Websites using HTTPS are considered to be more compliant with data protection regulations, such as GDPR (General Data Protection Regulation) and PCI-DSS (Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Prerequisites for Changing WordPress URL to HTTPS via Database</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before making any changes to the database, there are a few prerequisites you should ensure:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>SSL Certificate</strong>: Make sure that your SSL certificate is installed correctly on your WordPress website. You can get an SSL certificate from your web host, or you can use a free service like Let‚Äôs Encrypt. If you‚Äôre unsure whether your SSL certificate is properly installed, you can check by visiting your website with <code>https://</code> (for example, <code>https://www.yoursite.com</code>), and your browser should display a secure padlock symbol in the address bar.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Access to phpMyAdmin</strong>: To modify the database, you need access to phpMyAdmin, which is a database management tool provided by most web hosting providers. You can access phpMyAdmin through your hosting account‚Äôs cPanel.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Backup Your Database</strong>: <strong>Backing up your WordPress database is crucial</strong> before making any changes. In case something goes wrong, you can easily restore your website to its previous state. You can use plugins like UpdraftPlus or perform a manual backup via phpMyAdmin.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Steps to Change WordPress URL from HTTP to HTTPS in the Database</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once you‚Äôve ensured that the SSL certificate is installed and you‚Äôve backed up your website, you can begin the process of changing your WordPress URL from HTTP to HTTPS in the database. There are two main methods for doing this: directly editing the database using SQL queries and using phpMyAdmin to make the necessary changes manually.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 1: Log into Your Hosting Account</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The first step is to log into your hosting account. Typically, WordPress websites are hosted on platforms like cPanel, Plesk, or other hosting management systems. Once logged in, navigate to the <strong>phpMyAdmin</strong> tool. This tool allows you to interact with your WordPress database and make changes directly.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 2: Open phpMyAdmin and Select Your WordPress Database</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After logging in to phpMyAdmin, you‚Äôll see a list of all databases associated with your hosting account. Locate the database for your WordPress website, which is typically named something like <code>wp_database</code> or <code>yoursite_db</code>. Click on the database to open it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 3: Edit the wp_options Table</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the left-hand menu, under your WordPress database, locate and click on the <strong>wp_options</strong> table. This table holds several key configuration options for your WordPress site, including the <strong>siteurl</strong> and <strong>home</strong> values, which define your website‚Äôs URL.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Look for the <strong>siteurl</strong> and <strong>home</strong> rows. These are the values that define your website\'s base URL and need to be updated to HTTPS.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Click the <strong>Edit</strong> button (the pencil icon) next to each row, and you will be able to modify the <code>option_value</code> field.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>In the <strong>option_value</strong> field for both rows, change the <code>http://</code> to <code>https://</code>. For example, change:<code>http://yoursite.com</code> to <code>https://yoursite.com</code></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Once you‚Äôve made the changes, click <strong>Go</strong> to save the changes.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 4: Update URLs in the Database</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To fully switch your site to HTTPS, you need to update all internal references to your old HTTP URL throughout the WordPress database. These include URLs found in post content, media links, and other database tables. For this, you‚Äôll need to run a series of SQL queries.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here are the queries you should run in phpMyAdmin:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>UPDATE wp_options SET option_value = replace(option_value, \'http://codenskills.com\', \'https://codenskills.com\') WHERE option_name = \'home\' OR option_name = \'siteurl\';\n\nUPDATE wp_postmeta SET meta_value = replace(meta_value,\'http://codenskills.com\',\'https://codenskills.com\');\nUPDATE wp_posts SET guid = replace(guid, \'http://codenskills.com\',\'https://codenskills.com\');\n\nUPDATE wp_posts SET post_content = replace(post_content, \'http://codenskills.com\',\'https://codenskills.com\');\n\nUPDATE wp_posts SET pinged = REPLACE(pinged, \'http://codenskills.com\', \'https://codenskills.com\')WHERE pinged LIKE \'%http://codenskills.com%\';\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>These queries will replace all instances of the HTTP URL with the new HTTPS URL across various tables in your WordPress database.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 5: Update URLs in Page Builders (Optional)</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you are using a page builder like WPBakery or Elementor, you may need to run additional queries to replace URLs embedded in page builder content.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For WPBakery, run these queries:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>\nUPDATE wp_posts SET post_content = REPLACE(post_content, \'src=\"http://codenskills.com\', \'src=\"https://codenskills.com\')WHERE post_content LIKE \'%src=\"http://codenskills.com%\';\n\nUPDATE wp_posts SET post_content = REPLACE(post_content, \"src=\'http://codenskills.com\", \"src=\'https://codenskills.com\")WHERE post_content LIKE \"%src=\'http://codenskills.com%\";\n\nUPDATE wp_posts SET post_content = REPLACE(post_content, \'href=\"http://codenskills.com\', \'href=\"https://codenskills.com\')WHERE post_content LIKE \'%href=\"http://codenskills.com%\';\n\nUPDATE wp_posts SET post_content = REPLACE(post_content, \"href=\'http://codenskills.com\", \"href=\'https://codenskills.com\")WHERE post_content LIKE \"%href=\'http://codenskills.com%\";\n\n\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 6: Clear Cache and Verify Changes</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once you‚Äôve made the necessary database changes, you should clear your website‚Äôs cache to ensure that visitors see the updated HTTPS URLs. If you are using a caching plugin, such as W3 Total Cache or WP Super Cache, clear the cache from within the plugin settings.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Additionally, clear your browser cache to ensure that you‚Äôre seeing the most recent version of your website.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Finally, verify that the changes were successful by visiting your website using HTTPS. Check if the site loads without any security warnings and confirm that all internal links now use HTTPS.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-buttons\"><!-- wp:button -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-button\"><a class=\"wp-block-button__link wp-element-button\" href=\"https://codenskills.com/how-to-force-redirect-http-to-https-in-wordpress-via-htaccess/\">How to force redirect HTTP to HTTPS in WordPress via htaccess</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you have any caching plugins or services enabled, it\'s recommended to clear the cache after making changes to the database to ensure that your website displays correctly with the new URL. If you encounter any issues, you can restore the backup you made earlier and try again or seek help from a professional developer.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'How to change WordPress  URL HTTP to HTTPS  from database', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '33-revision-v1', '', '', '2025-02-06 12:29:53', '2025-02-06 12:29:53', '', 33, 'https://codenskills.com/?p=674', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
