void unintended data loss.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By mastering these commands, you can maintain a cleaner and more efficient Git history, making collaboration and debugging easier for your team.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-buttons\"><!-- wp:button -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-button\"><a class=\"wp-block-button__link wp-element-button\" href=\"https://codenskills.com/how-to-set-up-virtual-hosts-in-xampp-for-local-development/\">How to Set Up Virtual Hosts in XAMPP for Local Development</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Clearing Commits and Logs with Git Rebase', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '690-revision-v1', '', '', '2025-03-02 16:36:36', '2025-03-02 16:36:36', '', 690, 'https://codenskills.com/?p=693', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(695, 1, '2025-03-03 08:02:51', '2025-03-03 08:02:51', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>TWhen building a website, it\'s often useful to determine whether a link is external or internal. External links direct users to a different domain, whereas internal links keep them within the same site. To enhance user experience and SEO, many developers prefer opening external links in a new tab while keeping internal links unchanged.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In this article, we will explore how to check if a link is external using both <strong>jQuery</strong> and <strong>pure JavaScript</strong>. We will also discuss different approaches to handling external links for better usability.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Why Identify External Links?</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before diving into the code, let‚Äôs explore why identifying external links is important:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Better User Experience</strong> ‚Äì Keeping users on the same tab for internal links while opening external links in a new tab prevents them from losing track of your website.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>SEO Considerations</strong> ‚Äì Adding <code>rel=\"nofollow\"</code> to external links prevents search engines from following them, reducing the risk of passing link equity to unknown sites.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Security</strong> ‚Äì External links can be potential security risks. Identifying them allows developers to add security attributes like <code>rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"</code>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Checking If a Link is External Using jQuery</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>jQuery provides a simple way to loop through all <code>&lt;a&gt;</code> tags and check their hostname. Here‚Äôs a script that does this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;script src=\"https://code.jquery.com/jquery-3.6.0.min.js\">&lt;/script>\n&lt;script>\n  $(document).ready(function () {\n    var currentDomain = new RegExp(location.hostname);\n\n    $(\'a\').each(function () {\n      var link = $(this).attr(\'href\');\n\n      if (link &amp;&amp; !currentDomain.test(link)) {\n        $(this).attr(\'target\', \'_blank\').attr(\'rel\', \'noopener noreferrer\');\n      }\n    });\n  });\n&lt;/script>\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Explanation of the Code:</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>We create a <code>RegExp</code> object using the current domain (<code>location.hostname</code>).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>We loop through all <code>&lt;a></code> elements using <code>each()</code>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>If a link does <strong>not</strong> contain the current domain, it is considered external.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>We add the <code>target=\"_blank\"</code> attribute to open it in a new tab and <code>rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"</code> for security.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Checking If a Link is External Using Pure JavaScript</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you prefer not to use jQuery, you can achieve the same functionality using vanilla JavaScript:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;script>\n  document.addEventListener(\'DOMContentLoaded\', function () {\n    var links = document.querySelectorAll(\'a\');\n\n    links.forEach(function (link) {\n      if (link.hostname &amp;&amp; link.hostname !== window.location.hostname) {\n        link.setAttribute(\'target\', \'_blank\');\n        link.setAttribute(\'rel\', \'noopener noreferrer\');\n      }\n    });\n  });\n&lt;/script>\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>How This Works:</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>We wait for the <code>DOMContentLoaded</code> event to ensure the script runs after the page loads.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><code>querySelectorAll(\'a\')</code> selects all anchor tags.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>We use <code>forEach()</code> to loop through each link.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>If <code>link.hostname</code> is different from <code>window.location.hostname</code>, it is external.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>We then add the necessary attributes (<code>target=\"_blank\"</code> and <code>rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"</code>).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Enhancing External Link Security</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Apart from opening external links in a new tab, it‚Äôs important to consider security. Here are two key security attributes:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><code>rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"</code></strong><!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Prevents the new tab from accessing <code>window.opener</code>, which can be exploited in phishing attacks.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><code>noopener</code> prevents the new tab from controlling the original page.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><code>noreferrer</code> prevents referrer information from being sent.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list --></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong><code>rel=\"nofollow\"</code></strong><!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Tells search engines not to pass link equity to external sites, which is useful when linking to untrusted sources.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list --></li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>How to Add These Attributes Using JavaScript:</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>document.querySelectorAll(\'a\').forEach(link => {\n  if (link.hostname !== window.location.hostname) {\n    link.setAttribute(\'rel\', \'nofollow noopener noreferrer\');\n  }\n});</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Alternatively, you can use pure JavaScript with the following code:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>var links = document.querySelectorAll(\'a\');\nfor (var i = 0; i &lt; links.length; i++) {\n  if (links&#91;i].hostname !== window.location.hostname) {\n    links&#91;i].setAttribute(\'target\', \'_blank\');\n  }\n}\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Final Thoughts</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Checking if a link is external or internal is a simple but effective way to improve user experience, SEO, and security.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Key Takeaways:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Use <strong>JavaScript or jQuery</strong> to check if a link is external.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Open external links in a <strong>new tab</strong> (<code>target=\"_blank\"</code>) for better user experience.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Add <code>rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"</code> for <strong>security</strong> and <code>rel=\"nofollow\"</code> for <strong>SEO</strong>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Use <strong>CSS</strong> to visually highlight external links.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-buttons\"><!-- wp:button -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-button\"><a class=\"wp-block-button__link wp-element-button\" href=\"https://codenskills.com/how-to-disable-theme-editor-and-plugin-editor-in-wordpress-admin-panel/\">How to disable Theme Editor and Plugin Editor in the WordPress admin panel?</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons -->', 'Check if links are external with jQuery/javascript.', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '290-revision-v1', '', '', '2025-03-03 08:02:51', '2025-03-03 08:02:51', '', 290, 'https://codenskills.com/?p=695', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(697, 1, '2025-03-03 08:13:00', '2025-03-03 08:13:00', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you are building a WordPress theme and want to integrate a <strong>Bootstrap menu</strong>, you need to customize the WordPress menu structure. By default, WordPress generates a menu structure that doesn‚Äôt fully match Bootstrap\'s format. However, using the <strong>Walker Class</strong>, we can transform the WordPress menu into a Bootstrap-compatible menu.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In this article, we‚Äôll go step by step on how to use a <strong>custom Walker class</strong> to create a <strong>Bootstrap menu in WordPress</strong>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Why Use a Walker Class for Menus?</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A <strong>Walker Class</strong> in WordPress is a way to customize the HTML output of hierarchical structures such as menus, categories, and comments. In this case, we‚Äôll use a Walker class to modify the WordPress menu markup to align with <strong>Bootstrap\'s dropdown structure</strong>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 1: Define a Custom Walker Class in <code>functions.php</code></strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We will create a custom class named <code>submenu_wrapper</code> by extending the <code>Walker_Nav_Menu</code> class. This will help us customize the output of WordPress menus.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Add the following code to your <code>functions.php</code> file:</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>class submenu_wrapper extends Walker_Nav_Menu {\n    // Add classes to &lt;ul> sub-menus\n    function start_lvl( &amp;$output, $depth = 0, $args = array() ) {\n        $indent = ($depth > 0 ? str_repeat(\"\\t\", $depth) : \'\'); // Code indent\n        $display_depth = ($depth + 1); // First submenu is depth 0\n\n        // Define classes for sub-menus\n        $classes = array(\'dropdown-menu\');\n        $class_names = implode(\' \', $classes);\n\n        // Build the submenu HTML\n        if ($display_depth == 1) {\n            $output .= \"\\n\" . $indent . \'&lt;ul class=\"\' . $class_names . \'\">\' . \"\\n\";\n        } else {\n            $output .= \"\\n\" . $indent . \'&lt;ul class=\"\' . $class_names . \'\">\' . \"\\n\";\n        }\n    }\n}\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>What This Code Does:</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Extends the <code>Walker_Nav_Menu</code> class.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Modifies the <strong>submenu (<code>&lt;ul></code>) output</strong> by adding the Bootstrap class <code>dropdown-menu</code>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Ensures <strong>nested menus</strong> work correctly.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 2: Add Bootstrap-Compatible Classes to Menu Links</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To make our menu fully compatible with Bootstrap, we need to modify the <code>&lt;a&gt;</code> tags inside our menu items. WordPress provides the <code>nav_menu_link_attributes</code> filter to modify menu link attributes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Add the following function to your <code>functions.php</code> file:</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>add_filter(\'nav_menu_link_attributes\', \'anchor_menu_add_class\', 10, 4);\nfunction anchor_menu_add_class($atts, $item, $args, $depth = 0) {\n    // Check if the menu item has children and is at depth 0\n    if ($args->walker->has_children == 1 &amp;&amp; $depth === 0) {\n        $atts&#91;\'href\'] = !empty($item->url) ? $item->url : \'\';\n        $atts&#91;\'data-toggle\'] = \'dropdown\';\n        $atts&#91;\'class\'] = \'dropdown-toggle\';\n        $atts&#91;\'aria-haspopup\'] = \'true\';\n        $atts&#91;\'aria-expanded\'] = \'false\';\n    } elseif ($depth === 0) {\n        $atts&#91;\'href\'] = !empty($item->url) ? $item->url : \'\';\n        $atts&#91;\'class\'] = \'nav-link\';\n    } elseif ($depth === 1) {\n        $atts&#91;\'href\'] = !empty($item->url) ? $item->url : \'\';\n        $atts&#91;\'class\'] = \'dropdown-item\';\n    }\n    return $atts;\n}\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>What This Code Does:</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Adds Bootstrap‚Äôs <code>dropdown-toggle</code> class to parent menu items with children.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Ensures top-level items have the <code>nav-link</code> class.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Adds the <code>dropdown-item</code> class to submenu links.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Uses <code>data-toggle=\"dropdown\"</code> for Bootstrap functionality.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 3: Call the Walker Class in <code>header.php</code></strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now that we have our <strong>Walker Class</strong> and <strong>custom attributes for menu links</strong>, we need to call it when rendering the menu in <code>header.php</code>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Replace the default <code>wp_nav_menu()</code> function with the following:</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;?php \necho wp_nav_menu(array(\n    \'menu\' => \'Home Menu\',\n    \'menu_class\' => \'navbar-nav ml-auto\',\n    \'walker\' => new submenu_wrapper(),\n    \'container\' => false\n)); \n?>\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>What This Code Does:</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Calls the WordPress menu named <code>\"Home Menu\"</code>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Uses the <strong>custom walker class</strong> (<code>submenu_wrapper</code>).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Adds the Bootstrap class <code>navbar-nav ml-auto</code>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Removes the default <code>div</code> container (<code>container => false</code>).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 4: Add Active Class to the Current Menu Item</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To highlight the active menu item, WordPress assigns the class <code>current-menu-item</code>. However, we can make it more Bootstrap-friendly.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Add this code to <code>functions.php</code>:</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>add_filter(\'nav_menu_css_class\', \'add_active_class_to_menu\', 10, 2);\nfunction add_active_class_to_menu($classes, $item) {\n    if (in_array(\'current-menu-item\', $classes)) {\n        $classes&#91;] = \'active\';\n    }\n    return $classes;\n}\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>What This Code Does:</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Checks if the menu item has the <strong>current-menu-item</strong> class.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>If so, it adds the Bootstrap <code>active</code> class to highlight it.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 5: Add Bootstrap Navbar Structure</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Make sure your menu is wrapped inside the Bootstrap navbar structure in <code>header.php</code>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;nav class=\"navbar navbar-expand-lg navbar-light bg-light\">\n    &lt;a class=\"navbar-brand\" href=\"#\">Your Logo&lt;/a>\n    &lt;button class=\"navbar-toggler\" type=\"button\" data-toggle=\"collapse\" data-target=\"#navbarNav\"\n        aria-controls=\"navbarNav\" aria-expanded=\"false\" aria-label=\"Toggle navigation\">\n        &lt;span class=\"navbar-toggler-icon\">&lt;/span>\n    &lt;/button>\n    &lt;div class=\"collapse navbar-collapse\" id=\"navbarNav\">\n        &lt;?php \n        echo wp_nav_menu(array(\n            \'menu\' => \'Home Menu\',\n            \'menu_class\' => \'navbar-nav ml-auto\',\n            \'walker\' => new submenu_wrapper(),\n            \'container\' => false\n        )); \n        ?>\n    &lt;/div>\n&lt;/nav>\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Final Thoughts</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By following these steps, we have successfully converted a <strong>WordPress menu into a Bootstrap menu</strong> using the <strong>Walker Class</strong>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Key Features Implemented:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Used a <strong>Walker Class</strong> to modify the <strong>menu structure</strong>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Added Bootstrap classes (<code>dropdown-menu</code>, <code>dropdown-toggle</code>, <code>dropdown-item</code>).</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Integrated the menu into <strong>Bootstrap‚Äôs navbar</strong>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Added an <code>active</code> class to highlight the <strong>current menu item</strong>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":176,\"width\":\"823px\",\"height\":\"129px\",\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large is-resized\"><img src=\"https://codenskills.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/05/Screenshot_2021-05-27_18_29_48-1024x162.png\" alt=\"Bootstrap Menu\" class=\"wp-image-176\" style=\"width:823px;height:129px\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><br>   </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-buttons\"><!-- wp:button -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-button\"><a class=\"wp-block-button__link wp-element-button\" href=\"https://codenskills.com/how-to-add-active-class-in-wordpress-bootstrap-menu-using-hook/\">Add Active class in wordpress menu by hook </a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons -->', 'How To Convert HTML Bootstrap Menu In WordPress', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '39-revision-v1', '', '', '2025-03-03 08:13:00', '2025-03-03 08:13:00', '', 39, 'https://codenskills.com/?p=697', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(699, 1, '2025-03-03 09:37:04', '2025-03-03 09:37:04', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Breadcrumbs are an essential part of website navigation, improving <strong>user experience</strong> and <strong>SEO</strong>. They help users understand their location within your site and make it easier to navigate back to previous pages.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Instead of using a <strong>plugin</strong>, you can create breadcrumbs manually in WordPress by adding a custom function to your theme‚Äôs <code>functions.php</code> file. This guide will walk you through how to implement breadcrumbs in WordPress without a plugin.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Why Use Breadcrumbs?</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before diving into the implementation, let‚Äôs understand why breadcrumbs are beneficial:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li> <strong>Improves User Experience:</strong> Users can quickly navigate back to previous sections.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li> <strong>Boosts SEO:</strong> Search engines like Google use breadcrumbs to understand site structure.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li> <strong>Enhances Click-Through Rate (CTR):</strong> Breadcrumbs appear in search results, making them more appealing.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li> <strong>Reduces Bounce Rate:</strong> Users are encouraged to explore other pages instead of leaving.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 1: Add Breadcrumb Function in <code>functions.php</code></strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To create a custom breadcrumb trail, we need to define a function in the WordPress theme‚Äôs <code>functions.php</code> file.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Add the following code to your <code>functions.php</code> file:</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>function my_breadcrumbs() {\n  \n  $delimiter = \'‚Ä∫\'; // Separator between breadcrumb items\n  $home = \'Home\'; // Label for the home link\n  $currentBefore = \'&lt;li class=\"breadcrumb-item active\" aria-current=\"page\">\';\n  $currentAfter = \'&lt;/li>\';\n  \n  if (!is_home() &amp;&amp; !is_front_page() || is_paged()) {\n    \n    global $post;\n    $homeLink = get_bloginfo(\'url\');\n    echo \'&lt;ul class=\"breadcrumb\">\';\n    echo \'&lt;li class=\"breadcrumb-item\">&lt;a href=\"\' . $homeLink . \'\">\' . $home . \'&lt;/a>&lt;/li> \' . $delimiter . \' \';\n  \n    if (is_category()) {\n      global $wp_query;\n      $cat_obj = $wp_query->get_queried_object();\n      $thisCat = $cat_obj->term_id;\n      $thisCat = get_category($thisCat);\n      $parentCat = get_category($thisCat->parent);\n      if ($thisCat->parent != 0) echo(get_category_parents($parentCat, TRUE, \' \' . $delimiter . \' \'));\n      echo $currentBefore . single_cat_title(\'\', false) . $currentAfter;\n  \n    } elseif (is_single()) {\n      $cat = get_the_category();\n      $cat = $cat&#91;0];\n      echo \'&lt;li class=\"breadcrumb-item\">&lt;a href=\"\' . get_category_link($cat) . \'\">\' . $cat->name . \'&lt;/a>&lt;/li> \' . $delimiter . \' \';\n      echo $currentBefore . get_the_title() . $currentAfter;\n  \n    } elseif (is_page() &amp;&amp; !$post->post_parent) {\n      echo $currentBefore . get_the_title() . $currentAfter;\n  \n    } elseif (is_page() &amp;&amp; $post->post_parent) {\n      $parent_id = $post->post_parent;\n      $breadcrumbs = array();\n      while ($parent_id) {\n        $page = get_page($parent_id);\n        $breadcrumbs&#91;] = \'&lt;li class=\"breadcrumb-item\">&lt;a href=\"\' . get_permalink($page->ID) . \'\">\' . get_the_title($page->ID) . \'&lt;/a>&lt;/li>\';\n        $parent_id = $page->post_parent;\n      }\n      $breadcrumbs = array_reverse($breadcrumbs);\n      foreach ($breadcrumbs as $crumb) echo $crumb . \' \' . $delimiter . \' \';\n      echo $currentBefore . get_the_title() . $currentAfter;\n  \n    } elseif (is_search()) {\n      echo $currentBefore . \'Search results for \"\' . get_search_query() . \'\"\' . $currentAfter;\n  \n    } elseif (is_404()) {\n      echo $currentBefore . \'Error 404\' . $currentAfter;\n    }\n  \n    echo \'&lt;/ul>\';\n  }\n}\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 2: Call the Breadcrumb Function in <code>header.php</code></strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now that we have defined the breadcrumb function, we need to display it in the correct location on our WordPress site.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Place this code in <code>header.php</code> where you want the breadcrumbs to appear:</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;?php if (function_exists(\'my_breadcrumbs\')) my_breadcrumbs(); ?>\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This ensures that the breadcrumb navigation appears <strong>below the header</strong> or wherever you place this code.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 3: Style the Breadcrumbs with CSS</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To ensure the breadcrumbs match your site‚Äôs design, add the following CSS to your theme‚Äôs <code>style.css</code> file:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>.breadcrumb {\n  list-style: none;\n  padding: 10px 0;\n  background: #f8f9fa;\n  border-radius: 5px;\n  display: flex;\n  gap: 5px;\n}\n\n.breadcrumb li {\n  display: inline;\n  font-size: 14px;\n}\n\n.breadcrumb li a {\n  text-decoration: none;\n  color: #007bff;\n}\n\n.breadcrumb li a:hover {\n  text-decoration: underline;\n}\n\n.breadcrumb-item.active {\n  font-weight: bold;\n  color: #333;\n}\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>his CSS:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Styles the breadcrumb background.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Adds spacing between breadcrumb items.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Highlights the current page in <strong>bold</strong>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 4: Test the Breadcrumb Functionality</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To ensure everything works correctly, visit different pages on your WordPress site, such as:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>‚úÖ <strong>Homepage:</strong> Breadcrumbs should not appear.<br>‚úÖ <strong>Category Page:</strong> Should show ‚ÄúHome ‚Ä∫ Category Name.‚Äù<br>‚úÖ <strong>Single Post:</strong> Should show ‚ÄúHome ‚Ä∫ Category ‚Ä∫ Post Title.‚Äù<br>‚úÖ <strong>Page with Parent:</strong> Should show ‚ÄúHome ‚Ä∫ Parent Page ‚Ä∫ Current Page.‚Äù<br>‚úÖ <strong>Search Results:</strong> Should display ‚ÄúHome ‚Ä∫ Search results for: keyword.‚Äù<br>‚úÖ <strong>404 Page:</strong> Should display ‚ÄúHome ‚Ä∫ Error 404.‚Äù</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 5: Enhance Breadcrumb Functionality (Optional)</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To further improve the breadcrumbs, you can:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>1. Add Breadcrumbs to Yoast SEO (Without a Plugin)</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you are using <strong>Yoast SEO</strong>, you can integrate its built-in breadcrumb function:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;?php if ( function_exists(\'yoast_breadcrumb\') ) {\n  yoast_breadcrumb(\'&lt;ul class=\"breadcrumb\">\', \'&lt;/ul>\');\n} ?></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>2. Add Schema Markup for SEO</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To make breadcrumbs <strong>SEO-friendly</strong>, add Schema.org markup:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>echo \'&lt;ul class=\"breadcrumb\" itemscope itemtype=\"https://schema.org/BreadcrumbList\">\';\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Each breadcrumb item should be wrapped in:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;li itemprop=\"itemListElement\" itemscope itemtype=\"https://schema.org/ListItem\">\n  &lt;a itemprop=\"item\" href=\"your-url\">\n    &lt;span itemprop=\"name\">Your Page Name&lt;/span>\n  &lt;/a>\n  &lt;meta itemprop=\"position\" content=\"1\" />\n&lt;/li>\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This helps Google display breadcrumbs in search results.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Adding <strong>breadcrumbs without a plugin</strong> in WordPress is an effective way to improve <strong>navigation, user experience, and SEO</strong>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-buttons\"><!-- wp:button -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-button\"><a class=\"wp-block-button__link wp-element-button\" href=\"https://codenskills.com/how-to-convert-html-bootstrap-menu-in-wordpress/\">How to add active class in WordPress bootstrap menu using hook</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons -->', 'How to add breadcrumb in wordpress without plugin', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '74-revision-v1', '', '', '2025-03-03 09:37:04', '2025-03-03 09:37:04', '', 74, 'https://codenskills.com/?p=699', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
