(701, 1, '2025-03-03 09:37:44', '2025-03-03 09:37:44', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Breadcrumbs are an essential part of website navigation, improving <strong>user experience</strong> and <strong>SEO</strong>. They help users understand their location within your site and make it easier to navigate back to previous pages.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Instead of using a <strong>plugin</strong>, you can create breadcrumbs manually in WordPress by adding a custom function to your theme‚Äôs <code>functions.php</code> file. This guide will walk you through how to implement breadcrumbs in WordPress without a plugin.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Why Use Breadcrumbs?</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before diving into the implementation, let‚Äôs understand why breadcrumbs are beneficial:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li> <strong>Improves User Experience:</strong> Users can quickly navigate back to previous sections.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li> <strong>Boosts SEO:</strong> Search engines like Google use breadcrumbs to understand site structure.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li> <strong>Enhances Click-Through Rate (CTR):</strong> Breadcrumbs appear in search results, making them more appealing.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li> <strong>Reduces Bounce Rate:</strong> Users are encouraged to explore other pages instead of leaving.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 1: Add Breadcrumb Function in <code>functions.php</code></strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To create a custom breadcrumb trail, we need to define a function in the WordPress theme‚Äôs <code>functions.php</code> file.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Add the following code to your <code>functions.php</code> file:</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>function my_breadcrumbs() {\n  \n  $delimiter = \'‚Ä∫\'; // Separator between breadcrumb items\n  $home = \'Home\'; // Label for the home link\n  $currentBefore = \'&lt;li class=\"breadcrumb-item active\" aria-current=\"page\">\';\n  $currentAfter = \'&lt;/li>\';\n  \n  if (!is_home() &amp;&amp; !is_front_page() || is_paged()) {\n    \n    global $post;\n    $homeLink = get_bloginfo(\'url\');\n    echo \'&lt;ul class=\"breadcrumb\">\';\n    echo \'&lt;li class=\"breadcrumb-item\">&lt;a href=\"\' . $homeLink . \'\">\' . $home . \'&lt;/a>&lt;/li> \' . $delimiter . \' \';\n  \n    if (is_category()) {\n      global $wp_query;\n      $cat_obj = $wp_query->get_queried_object();\n      $thisCat = $cat_obj->term_id;\n      $thisCat = get_category($thisCat);\n      $parentCat = get_category($thisCat->parent);\n      if ($thisCat->parent != 0) echo(get_category_parents($parentCat, TRUE, \' \' . $delimiter . \' \'));\n      echo $currentBefore . single_cat_title(\'\', false) . $currentAfter;\n  \n    } elseif (is_single()) {\n      $cat = get_the_category();\n      $cat = $cat&#91;0];\n      echo \'&lt;li class=\"breadcrumb-item\">&lt;a href=\"\' . get_category_link($cat) . \'\">\' . $cat->name . \'&lt;/a>&lt;/li> \' . $delimiter . \' \';\n      echo $currentBefore . get_the_title() . $currentAfter;\n  \n    } elseif (is_page() &amp;&amp; !$post->post_parent) {\n      echo $currentBefore . get_the_title() . $currentAfter;\n  \n    } elseif (is_page() &amp;&amp; $post->post_parent) {\n      $parent_id = $post->post_parent;\n      $breadcrumbs = array();\n      while ($parent_id) {\n        $page = get_page($parent_id);\n        $breadcrumbs&#91;] = \'&lt;li class=\"breadcrumb-item\">&lt;a href=\"\' . get_permalink($page->ID) . \'\">\' . get_the_title($page->ID) . \'&lt;/a>&lt;/li>\';\n        $parent_id = $page->post_parent;\n      }\n      $breadcrumbs = array_reverse($breadcrumbs);\n      foreach ($breadcrumbs as $crumb) echo $crumb . \' \' . $delimiter . \' \';\n      echo $currentBefore . get_the_title() . $currentAfter;\n  \n    } elseif (is_search()) {\n      echo $currentBefore . \'Search results for \"\' . get_search_query() . \'\"\' . $currentAfter;\n  \n    } elseif (is_404()) {\n      echo $currentBefore . \'Error 404\' . $currentAfter;\n    }\n  \n    echo \'&lt;/ul>\';\n  }\n}\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 2: Call the Breadcrumb Function in <code>header.php</code></strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now that we have defined the breadcrumb function, we need to display it in the correct location on our WordPress site.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Place this code in <code>header.php</code> where you want the breadcrumbs to appear:</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;?php if (function_exists(\'my_breadcrumbs\')) my_breadcrumbs(); ?>\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This ensures that the breadcrumb navigation appears <strong>below the header</strong> or wherever you place this code.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 3: Style the Breadcrumbs with CSS</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To ensure the breadcrumbs match your site‚Äôs design, add the following CSS to your theme‚Äôs <code>style.css</code> file:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>.breadcrumb {\n  list-style: none;\n  padding: 10px 0;\n  background: #f8f9fa;\n  border-radius: 5px;\n  display: flex;\n  gap: 5px;\n}\n\n.breadcrumb li {\n  display: inline;\n  font-size: 14px;\n}\n\n.breadcrumb li a {\n  text-decoration: none;\n  color: #007bff;\n}\n\n.breadcrumb li a:hover {\n  text-decoration: underline;\n}\n\n.breadcrumb-item.active {\n  font-weight: bold;\n  color: #333;\n}\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>his CSS:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Styles the breadcrumb background.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Adds spacing between breadcrumb items.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Highlights the current page in <strong>bold</strong>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 4: Test the Breadcrumb Functionality</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To ensure everything works correctly, visit different pages on your WordPress site, such as:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li> <strong>Homepage:</strong> Breadcrumbs should not appear.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li> <strong>Category Page:</strong> Should show ‚ÄúHome ‚Ä∫ Category Name.‚Äù</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li> <strong>Single Post:</strong> Should show ‚ÄúHome ‚Ä∫ Category ‚Ä∫ Post Title.‚Äù</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li> <strong>Page with Parent:</strong> Should show ‚ÄúHome ‚Ä∫ Parent Page ‚Ä∫ Current Page.‚Äù</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li> <strong>Search Results:</strong> Should display ‚ÄúHome ‚Ä∫ Search results for: keyword.‚Äù</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li> <strong>404 Page:</strong> Should display ‚ÄúHome ‚Ä∫ Error 404.‚Äù</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 5: Enhance Breadcrumb Functionality (Optional)</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To further improve the breadcrumbs, you can:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>1. Add Breadcrumbs to Yoast SEO (Without a Plugin)</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you are using <strong>Yoast SEO</strong>, you can integrate its built-in breadcrumb function:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;?php if ( function_exists(\'yoast_breadcrumb\') ) {\n  yoast_breadcrumb(\'&lt;ul class=\"breadcrumb\">\', \'&lt;/ul>\');\n} ?></code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>2. Add Schema Markup for SEO</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To make breadcrumbs <strong>SEO-friendly</strong>, add Schema.org markup:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>echo \'&lt;ul class=\"breadcrumb\" itemscope itemtype=\"https://schema.org/BreadcrumbList\">\';\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Each breadcrumb item should be wrapped in:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;li itemprop=\"itemListElement\" itemscope itemtype=\"https://schema.org/ListItem\">\n  &lt;a itemprop=\"item\" href=\"your-url\">\n    &lt;span itemprop=\"name\">Your Page Name&lt;/span>\n  &lt;/a>\n  &lt;meta itemprop=\"position\" content=\"1\" />\n&lt;/li>\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This helps Google display breadcrumbs in search results.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Adding <strong>breadcrumbs without a plugin</strong> in WordPress is an effective way to improve <strong>navigation, user experience, and SEO</strong>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-buttons\"><!-- wp:button -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-button\"><a class=\"wp-block-button__link wp-element-button\" href=\"https://codenskills.com/how-to-convert-html-bootstrap-menu-in-wordpress/\">How to add active class in WordPress bootstrap menu using hook</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons -->', 'How to add breadcrumb in wordpress without plugin', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '74-revision-v1', '', '', '2025-03-03 09:37:44', '2025-03-03 09:37:44', '', 74, 'https://codenskills.com/?p=701', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(703, 1, '2025-03-03 09:46:54', '2025-03-03 09:46:54', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>CSV (Comma-Separated Values) files are widely used for storing and exchanging structured data. Inserting data from a CSV file into a <strong>MySQL database</strong> is a common requirement for web applications. This article explains how to <strong>import multiple records</strong> from a CSV file into a MySQL database using <strong>PHP</strong>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 1: Create a MySQL Database and Table</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before inserting data, we need to create a MySQL table that matches the structure of our CSV file.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Run the following SQL query to create a sample table:</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>CREATE DATABASE csv_database;\nUSE csv_database;\n\nCREATE TABLE users (\n    id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,\n    name VARCHAR(100),\n    email VARCHAR(100)\n);\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This table has three columns: <code>id</code>, <code>name</code>, and <code>email</code>, where <code>id</code> is an auto-incremented primary key.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 2: Insert CSV Data Using PHP</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>PHP provides built-in functions to read CSV files and insert data into a MySQL database.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Basic PHP Code to Insert CSV Data into MySQL</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;?php\n\n// Database connection\n$mysqli = new mysqli(\"localhost\", \"root\", \"password\", \"csv_database\");\n\nif ($mysqli->connect_error) {\n    die(\"Connection failed: \" . $mysqli->connect_error);\n}\n\n// Open CSV file\n$file = fopen(\"data.csv\", \"r\");\n\n// Skip the first row if it contains column headers\nfgetcsv($file);\n\n// Read each row and insert it into the database\nwhile (($row = fgetcsv($file, 1000, \",\")) !== FALSE) {\n    $sql = \"INSERT INTO users (name, email) VALUES (\'$row&#91;0]\', \'$row&#91;1]\')\";\n    $mysqli->query($sql);\n}\n\n// Close file and database connection\nfclose($file);\n$mysqli->close();\n\necho \"Data imported successfully!\";\n?>\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Explanation of the PHP Code:</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Connects to MySQL</strong> using <code>mysqli</code>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Opens the CSV file</strong> using <code>fopen()</code>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Reads each row</strong> using <code>fgetcsv()</code>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Inserts data into the database</strong> using an <code>INSERT INTO</code> query.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Closes the file and database connection</strong> after completion.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 3: Optimize for Large CSV Files</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For large CSV files, inserting data <strong>row by row</strong> can be slow. Instead, we can <strong>bulk insert</strong> multiple rows in a single query to improve performance.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Optimized PHP Code for Bulk CSV Import</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;?php\n\n$mysqli = new mysqli(\"localhost\", \"root\", \"password\", \"csv_database\");\n\n$file = fopen(\"data.csv\", \"r\");\n$values = &#91;];\n\n// Skip the first row if it contains column headers\nfgetcsv($file);\n\nwhile (($row = fgetcsv($file, 1000, \",\")) !== FALSE) {\n    $values&#91;] = \"(\'\" . implode(\"\',\'\", array_map(\'addslashes\', $row)) . \"\')\";\n}\n\n// Bulk insert query\nif (!empty($values)) {\n    $sql = \"INSERT INTO users (name, email) VALUES \" . implode(\",\", $values);\n    $mysqli->query($sql);\n}\n\nfclose($file);\n$mysqli->close();\n\necho \"Bulk data imported successfully!\";\n?>\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Why Use Bulk Insert?</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Inserts multiple rows in one query</strong>, significantly improving speed.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>Reduces database connection overhead</strong>, especially for large datasets.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Step 4: Test the Data Import</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After running the PHP script, check if the data has been inserted correctly by running the following SQL query:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>SELECT * FROM users;\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If everything is set up correctly, you should see the imported data in your database.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Best Practices for CSV Data Import in PHP</strong></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>‚úÖ <strong>Use Bulk Insert:</strong> It improves performance when handling large CSV files.<br>‚úÖ <strong>Validate Data Before Importing:</strong> Ensure the CSV file has the correct format.<br>‚úÖ <strong>Optimize Database Indexing:</strong> Indexing speeds up queries after data insertion.<br>‚úÖ <strong>Handle Special Characters:</strong> Use <code>addslashes()</code> to prevent errors.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:buttons -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-buttons\"><!-- wp:button -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-button\"><a class=\"wp-block-button__link wp-element-button\" href=\"https://codenskills.com/wp-custom-post-type-query-in-wordpress/\">WP Custom Post Type Query In WordPress</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button --></div>\n<!-- /wp:buttons -->', 'How To Insert Multiple data in the database from CSV', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '158-revision-v1', '', '', '2025-03-03 09:46:54', '2025-03-03 09:46:54', '', 158, 'https://codenskills.com/?p=703', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
