(761, 1, '2025-04-01 12:15:44', '2025-04-01 06:45:44', '<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"\"} -->\n<p>JWT tokens are widely used for secure user authentication and data exchange. This article explains how to build a simple JWT authentication system in PHP using Composer and PSR-4 autoloading.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"\"} -->\n<p>Start by setting up a clean project structure with an <code>index.php</code> as the entry point, a <code>composer.json</code> to manage dependencies, and a <code>src/</code> directory for your core classes like <code>JwtManager</code>. This structure leverages PSR-4 to automatically load classes via Composer.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"\"} -->\n<p>The <code>JwtManager</code> class creates, validates, and decodes JWTs. It constructs a token by encoding a header (with algorithm and token type) and a payload (containing user data and expiration time) using a base64 URL-safe method. Then, it generates a signature with HMAC SHA-256 using your secret key, combining these components into a single token.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"\"} -->\n<p>The <code>validateToken</code> method splits the token, decodes the signature, and verifies it against a newly generated signature. The <code>decodeToken</code> method extracts and decodes the payload for further processing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"\"} -->\n<p>Composer‚Äôs autoloading (via <code>composer dump-autoload</code>) ensures new classes in <code>src/</code> are automatically available, promoting a modular codebase. In your <code>index.php</code>, include Composer‚Äôs autoloader, instantiate <code>JwtManager</code> with your secret key, create a token with a payload, and validate it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"\"} -->\n<p>This streamlined approach results in a robust, scalable, and secure JWT-based authentication system, ideal for both small projects and larger applications.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"\"} -->\n<p>JSON Web Tokens (JWT) are a secure method for transmitting information between parties. In this guide, we‚Äôll create a basic JWT system using PHP, Composer, and the PSR-4 autoloading standard.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4,\"className\":\"\"} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>Project Structure</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To generate your Composer configuration and install Guzzle HTTP, run the following commands in your project directory:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>Composer init\ncomposer require guzzlehttp/guzzle</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"\"} -->\n<p>Organize your project as follows:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>jwt-php/\n‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ composer.json\n‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ index.php\n‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ src/\n‚îÇ   ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ JwtManager.php\n‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ vendor/</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\"><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>composer.json:</strong> Defines autoloading and any dependencies.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>index.php:</strong> Acts as the entry point.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><strong>src/JwtManager.php:</strong> Contains the core JWT logic.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4,\"className\":\"\"} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>composer.json</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"\"} -->\n<p>Configure PSR-4 autoloading in your <code>composer.json</code>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>{\n    \"autoload\": {\n        \"psr-4\": {\n            \"App\\\\\": \"src/\"\n        }\n    }\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Run the following command to generate the autoloader:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>composer dump-autoload</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4,\"className\":\"\"} -->\n<h4 class=\"wp-block-heading\"><strong>JwtManager Class</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"className\":\"\"} -->\n<p>Create <code>src/JwtManager.php</code> with the following content:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;?php\nnamespace App;\n\nclass JwtManager\n{\n    private $secretKey;\n\n    public function __construct($secretKey)\n    {\n        $this->secretKey = $secretKey;\n    }\n\n    public function createToken($payload)\n    {\n        $header = json_encode(&#91;\"alg\" => \"HS256\", \"typ\" => \"JWT\"]);\n        $payload = json_encode($payload);\n        $base64UrlHeader = $this->base64UrlEncode($header);\n        $base64UrlPayload = $this->base64UrlEncode($payload);\n        $signature = hash_hmac(\'sha256\', $base64UrlHeader . \'.\' . $base64UrlPayload, $this->secretKey, true);\n        $base64UrlSignature = $this->base64UrlEncode($signature);\n        return $base64UrlHeader . \'.\' . $base64UrlPayload . \'.\' . $base64UrlSignature;\n    }\n\n    private function base64UrlEncode($data)\n    {\n        $base64 = base64_encode($data);\n        $base64Url = strtr($base64, \'+/\', \'-_\');\n        return rtrim($base64Url, \'=\');\n    }\n\n    private function base64UrlDecode($data)\n    {\n        $base64 = strtr($data, \'-_\', \'+/\');\n        $padding = strlen($base64) % 4;\n        if ($padding) {\n            $base64 .= str_repeat(\'=\', 4 - $padding);\n        }\n        return base64_decode($base64);\n    }\n\n    public function validateToken($token)\n    {\n        list($header, $payload, $signature) = explode(\'.\', $tok